<HEADLINE> U.S. Urged to return Cuban Boy Immediately </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, April 17 (Xinhua) -- A spokeswoman of the Vietnamese
Foreign Ministry Monday demands that the United States immediately
return Cuban Boy Elian Gonzales so that he can reunite with his
father.
</P>
<P>
Spokeswoman of the Vietnamese Foreign Ministry Phan Thuy Thanh
made the demand when she was answering a question on Vietnam's
latest viewpoint regarding this matter.
</P>
<P>
She affirmed Vietnam's consistent stance of resolute demand
that the United States immediately end the anti-Cuban embargo and
strictly observe the Immigration Agreement signed in 1994 and 1995
between the governments of Cuba and the United States, under which
the United States pledged to return to Cuba all illegal Cuban
deportees. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000418.0003 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Vietnam, Singapore to Boost Comprehensive Cooperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, April 17 (Xinhua) -- Vietnam's Permanent Deputy Prime
Minister Nguyen Tan Dung and visiting Singaporean Deputy Prime
Minister Lee Hsien Loong held talks here Monday, agreeing to boost
comprehensive cooperation between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Lee, accompanied by a number of Singaporean senior officials,
arrived here Monday afternoon for a four-day official visit to
Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
During the talks, the two deputy prime ministers expressed
their satisfaction at the quick and fine development of the
friendship and comprehensive cooperation between Vietnam and
Singapore, especially after the March 1999 official visit to
Singapore by Vietnamese President Tran Duc Luong.
</P>
<P>
Dung and Lee agreed that the two sides should promote the
exchange of high-level delegations and contacts between business
people of the two countries, maintain existing cooperative
mechanisms and effectively implement the two countries' high-level
agreements and other accords which were signed at the 5th session
of the Vietnam-Singapore Cooperation Commission.
</P>
<P>
Dung affirmed that Vietnam will pursue the policy of attaching
importance to boosting and expanding its friendship and
comprehensive cooperation with Singapore in the framework of the
two countries' bilateral ties and between ASEAN member countries'
cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Lee affirmed that Singapore would continue supporting its
business people to promote investment in and trade with Vietnam.
Singapore is ready to share with Vietnam its experiences in
training, infrastructure construction, finance and banking,
development strategy, and international integration.
</P>
<P>
The two sides also discussed regional and international issues
of common concern.
</P>
<P>
By 1999, Singapore had become the biggest investor in Vietnam
with 234 projects worth more than 6.7 billion U.S. dollars and
Vietnam's second biggest trading partner with two-way trade
reaching about 2.7 billion dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
