<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran Bases Economic Plan on Attracting Foreign Investments </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, April 18 (Xinhua) -- Iran's Third Economic Development
Plan (2000-2005) is based on attracting foreign investments,
boosting foreign trade, and also technical and economic cooperation
with other countries, officials said here on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Iran has to reach an economic growth rate of 6 percent in the
five years to solve the problem of unemployment, currently as high
as 16 percent, according to Masoud Nili, deputy director of
economic affairs at the Plan and Budget Organization.
</P>
<P>
Briefing foreign ambassadors and representatives here on Iran's
third five-year plan, Nili said Iran needs an annual growth rate of
7.1 percent of investments to achieve the economic goal.
</P>
<P>
The government must realize the advantages for and set
regulations to facilitate foreign investments in Iran, he noted.
</P>
<P>
The total volume of Iran's costs in the program is estimated at
112 billion U.S. dollars, and the government has been allowed to
use 20 billion dollars from foreign credits, Mohammad Hussein
Adeli, deputy foreign minister in economic affairs, said on the
same occasion.
</P>
<P>
He considered developing non-oil exports and providing
investment security via introducing a framework with a legal
support as perspectives of Iran's new development plan.
</P>
<P>
According to the plan, endorsed by the parliament and the
Council of Guardians recently, the total imports of Iran will be
112.4 billion dollars during the period.
</P>
<P>
The revenues derived from oil exports, non-oil exports and
services would reach 64.1 billion dollars, 34.8 billion dollars and
6.2 billion dollars respectively during the five-year period.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
