<DOCNO> XIE20000418.0012 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iraq, UAE Discuss Opening Land Transport Line </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, April 18 (Xinhua) -- Officials from Iraq and the United
Arab Emirates (UAE) have held talks on opening up a land transport
line beside the already-existed sea route between the two
countries, a report said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The move is expected to greatly facilitate the bilateral trade
as well as trade among countries of the Gulf region, said Mohammad
Sabbar Al-Mosawi, general director of the Iraqi Land Transport
Company subordinate to the Iraqi Ministry of Transport and
Communication.
</P>
<P>
The issue was touched upon in a recent meeting between Al-Mosawi
and representatives from the Jawan Transport Company of the UAE.
</P>
<P>
The trade volume between Iraq and the UAE, within the framework
of the U.N. oil-for-food program, has reached 400 million U.S.
dollars, said the report.
</P>
<P>
Under the U.N. program, Iraq is allowed to sell a certain amount
of oil and use part of the revenues to import food, medicines and
other humanitarian goods for its people, who have been under
crippling U.N. sanctions ever since Iraq's 1990 invasion of Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
In the coming weeks, the UAE is expected to reopen its embassy,
which has been closed since the 1991 Gulf War, in the Iraqi capital
Baghdad.
</P>
<P>
Iraq will also reopen its consulate in Dubai, the commercial
center of the UAE.
</P>
<P>
UAE President Sheikh Zayed Bin Sultan Al-Nahyan has called for
lifting the trade embargo on Iraq, stressing the need to end the
sufferings of the Iraqi people and restore normal relations among
Arab nations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000418.0013 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cyprus Seeks for Political Solution to Internal Dispute, EU Accession </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, April 18 (Xinhua) -- Cyprus Foreign Minister Ioannis
Kasoulides said here Tuesday that the Cyprus government aims to
find a just and viable solution to the Cyprus issue and to work for
accession to the European Union (EU).
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the 17th meeting of the EU-Cyprus Joint
Parliamentary Committee, Kasoulides reiterated that the two
objectives are two parallel courses "which aim at strengthening
each other".
</P>
<P>
The two-day meeting opened here Monday to mainly discuss the
political situation in Cyprus, current EU-Cyprus relations and
Cyprus' accession negotiations with the EU.
</P>
<P>
Referring to the U.N.-sponsored peace talks on the Cyprus issue,
Kasoulides criticized Turkish Cypriot leader Rauf Denktash for
expecting to have his preconditions met before engaging in serious
negotiations.
</P>
<P>
Denktash has been asking for recognition of his breakaway state
in northern Cyprus, now recognized only by Turkey, and the
withdrawal of Cyprus' application for EU membership.
</P>
<P>
The eastern Mediterranean island has remained divided into the
Turkish Cypriots-controlled north and the Greek Cypriots-dominated
south since 1974 when Turkey invaded and occupied the northern
third in the wake of a failed pro-Athens coup in Nicosia.
</P>
<P>
Two rounds of U.N.-sponsored indirect talks between the two
sides were held last December in New York and in February in
Geneva, and a third round is due to begin on May 23 in New York.
The talks were aimed at preparing the ground for substantive
negotiations which may bring the two communities together.
</P>
<P>
Kasoulides said that now is the time for serious negotiations to
pave the way for a final solution to the Cyprus issue.
</P>
<P>
He assured the European parliamentarians attending the meeting
that the Cyprus government will always be positive and constructive
in the search of a solution.
</P>
<P>
"The possibility of refusing Cyprus' EU entry would be a severe
blow to the effort for stability in the eastern Mediterranean,"
Kasoulides warned. 
</P>
</TEXT>
