<DOCNO> XIE20000418.0014 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lebanese Guerrilla Rockets Hit Israeli North </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, April 18 (Xinhua) -- Several guerrilla rockets hit
settlements in northern Israel along the border with Lebanon, but
no casualties were reported yet, Israel Defense Forces officers
said Tuesday evening.
</P>
<P>
At least 30 Russian-made Katyusha rockets were fired by Lebanese
Hezbollah guerrillas, who have been fighting to end Israeli
occupation in south Lebanon since early 1980s, but only three or
four of them landed at the entrance to two Jewish settlements in
western Galilee, the officers in Jerusalem revealed.
</P>
<P>
There were reports of damages to an electric company
transformer, while most communities' leaders worried that the
rocket attack will harm local tourism in the Jewish Passover
Holiday that begins Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
IDF officers said the army has not ordered local residents to
lock themselves into bomb shelters or their basements, and the
situation in the north is quiet. But they will watch out for any
further attacks.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, it was reported that the condition of the IDF soldier
injured in the Israeli-occupied security zone in south Lebanon
earlier in the day is more serious than previously announced.
</P>
<P>
The soldier, who reportedly had sustained light injuries from an
Hezbollah anti-tank rocket, was diagnosed later as having a
fractured skull.
</P>
<P>
He was transferred to Haifa's Rambam Hospital, a hospital having
more advanced medical instruments than battleground aid stations,
for an emergency surgery.
</P>
<P>
However, his condition remains stable and his life is not at
risk, according to doctors in the hospital.
</P>
<P>
Hezbollah, who had killed seven IDF soldiers and wounded dozens
since the beginning of this year, has claimed responsibility for
both incidents.
</P>
<P>
The group launched a series of attacks on IDF and Israeli-backed
South Lebanon Army (SLA) outposts in the occupied buffer zone in
retaliation for Israeli artillery strikes earlier, which killed a
Syrian civilian worker and wounded his three colleagues.
</P>
<P>
The zone was set up by Israel in 1985 with a self-claimed aim to
protect its north from cross-border guerrilla attacks. However, the
fierce fighting of Hezbollah and other resistant militias had
forced Israel to seek an exit way from the zone.
</P>
<P>
Last month, Israel's cabinet adopted a proposal submitted by
Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak to carry out withdrawal from the
zone to the international border by July, with or without a peace
deal with Syria, the major power broker in Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Israeli Foreign Minister David Levy also made the plan
internationally official after sending a letter to United Nations
Secretary General Kofi Annan regarding the pullback.
</P>
<P>
However, some strategy analysts had warned that Hezbollah, which
is backed by Syria and Iran, will not keep Israel's northern border
quiet in the case of a pullout without agreements.
</P>
<P>
Barak expressed his determination to retaliate any such attacks
in the future by saying several times in the past few weeks that he
does not recommend any sides to test Israel's strains on the issue.
</P>
<P>
Earlier in the year, Israeli troops struck at suspected
Hezbollah targets and Lebanese civilian infrastructure sites in a
reprisal attacks, wounding at least two dozen civilians and
leading to a total damage cost at 200 million U.S. dollars.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
