<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Blair Travels to N.Ireland, Trying to End Peace Deadlock </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 18 (Xinhua)-- British Prime Minister Tony Blair
is visiting Northern Ireland on Tuesday in an attempt to breathe
new life into the deadlocked peace process.
</P>
<P>
Senior officials from British and Irish governments have been
trying to work out a formula which would allow the re-
establishment of the political institutions in Northern Ireland.
</P>
<P>
There is no suggestion Blair's visit will mark any major
breakthrough, but he will hold face-to-face discussions with
political leaders concerning the peace process in that region.
</P>
<P>
Blair's spokesman said he would not take any "blueprint" that
the parties could use to help resolve the impasse between
unionists and republicans over the issues of paramilitary arms and
sharing power.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister wants to "take stock" of the current
difficult situation with the key players, the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
This is Blair's first trip to Northern Ireland in nine months.
He will then travel to the Irish capital city of Dublin to meet
Irish Prime Minister Bertie Ahern.
</P>
<P>
Ulster Unionist leader David Trimble said he expected Blair
demand assurances from republicans that there would be no return
to violence.
</P>
<P>
Speaking on BBC Radio Ulster, he also said he wanted Blair to
persuade the Irish government to put pressure on Sinn Fein and the
IRA to fulfill their obligations under the agreement.
</P>
<P>
"Problems all come back to the same point, the absolute refusal
of republicans to recognize they too must change. This whole
prospect is about creating a new Northern Ireland, the old is
going to fade away," Trimble said.
</P>
<P>
"That means the old paramilitarism and old terrorism - we don't
want to see that in the future we want to construct," he added.
</P>
<P>
Sinn Fein's Mitchel McLaughlin said that if a breakthrough was
to be achieved over the suspension of the institutions, his party
would need to know that devolution was not "an experiment".
</P>
<P>
He said republicans needed to know it was not being implemented
for a "trial period, but is the real thing".
</P>
<P>
He said Sinn Fein would require in writing a "guarantee that
neither Northern Ireland Secretary Peter Mandelson nor any other
Secretary of State would ever again activate legislation
suspending the devolved institutions".  
</P>
</TEXT>
