<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NASA And NCI Jointly Develop Microscopic Medicine </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 18 (Xinhua) -- Imagine ingesting a capsule
containing microscopic sensors to detect, diagnose and treat
disease inside the human body.
</P>
<P>
It sounds like fiction. However, NASA, in collaboration with
National Cancer Institute (NCI), is working to turn this vision
into "science fact."
</P>
<P>
NASA and National Cancer Institute have reached an agreement in
mid-April to develop new biomedical technologies that can detect,
diagnose and treat disease on Earth and in space.
</P>
<P>
The joint collaboration comes as NASA and NCI each move forward
with historic initiatives requiring major advances in available
technology.
</P>
<P>
NCI is attempting to define cancer for the first time based on
the unique molecular characteristics of tumors.
</P>
<P>
NASA is seeking to develop a new form of patient care - "
microscopic explorers" -- that would travel through the human body
looking for disease. This technology will allow NASA to monitor
astronaut health and treat conditions in space, where medical test
capabilities and communication with Earth will be limited. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
