<HEADLINE> Hundreds of Birds Found Dead in Newfoundland </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, April 18 (Xinhua) -- At least 500 gulls have been found
dead with evidence of poisoning since the weekend in St. John's,
Newfoundland.
</P>
<P>
Dumped human food may have caused the sudden deaths of the
seabirds, local chief veterinarian Hugh Whitney said in his
initial report released Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
"A lot of them have human food in their mouths," such as bits
of hot dogs, potatoes, meat, peas and beans, he said after
examining the bodies of the dead birds.
</P>
<P>
"That seems to be the one common factor so far," he stated,
adding there are forensic clues for another incidence of botulism.
</P>
<P>
Tens of thousands of ducks and shorebirds have died of avian
botulism at Whitewater Lake, Manitoba since 1996, with up to 117,
000 birds found dead in the year alone.
</P>
<P>
The Canadian Wildlife Service is conducting a study to examine
the causes of avian botulism outbreaks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
