<HEADLINE> European Stocks Follow Wall Street Up </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 18 (Xinhua) -- Europe's leading stock markets
closed higher Tuesday, bolstered by signs of a continued rebound
in the Nasdaq composite index and despite concerns about the
region's inflation pressure.
</P>
<P>
London share prices have surged, fallen back and firmed again
in another turbulent day on the markets. The FTSE 100 rose 79.4
points, or 1.3 percent, to 6,074.
</P>
<P>
Worries over possible interest rate rises are continuing to
trouble investors, who are not convinced that the worst of the
falls has passed.
</P>
<P>
UK March inflation figures showed a record low for the
underlying rate of 2.0 percent, but the headline rate of 2.6
percent, which includes mortgage interest payments, was slightly
higher than economists had predicted.
</P>
<P>
The Xetra Dax in Frankfurt edged up 9.35 points, or 0.1 percent,
to 7,196.49. Banks were among the leading decliners on the Dax,
with FHVM falling 1.8 percent and FDRB down 2.3 percent. But FCBK
bucked the trend, rising 2.8 percent.
</P>
<P>
Shares in Paris ended with good gains as U.S. stock indices
continued to recover from last week's selloff while France Telecom
surged.
</P>
<P>
The CAC-40 benchmark ended up 86.9 or 1.43 percent at 6,147.44
points, with gainers outpacing decliners 21-19. 
</P>
</TEXT>
