<HEADLINE> Cuban Proposal to Relax Turtle Trade Rejected </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, April 18 (Xinhua) -- Cuba's request to relax the ban
on the turtle trade was rejected Tuesday at the 11th Conference
of the Convention on International Trade in Endangered Species.
</P>
<P>
Delegates at the 150-country conference voted down a proposal
allowing Cuba to sell 6,900 kg of hawksbill shells to japan in a
one-off auction.
</P>
<P>
Cuba needed a two-thirds majority but fell short with 66
nations voting in favour, 38 against and 15 abstained.
</P>
<P>
Cuba withdrew the request for an annual export quota of 500
hawksbill specimens in the face of strong opposition just before
the vote.
</P>
<P>
However, it is likely that cuba will ask for another vote at a
plenary session on Wednesday or Thursday since it failed
narrowly.
</P>
<P>
The trade ban in Hawksbill turtles in the Atlantic was imposed
in 1975.
</P>
<P>
The Hawksbill shells are used for jewellery and ornaments and
hides are cured to make leather boots.
</P>
<P>
Hawksbills can weigh up to 60 kg in weight and their shells are
 patterned with streaks of amber, yellow and brown, making them
the most sought after among the world's seven species of marine
turtle. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
