<HEADLINE> Ethiopia Makes Water, Sanitation Project Master Plan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, April 18 (Xinhua) -- Ethiopia is making a master
plan to promote water resources utilization and to improve
sanitation in the country, a senior official said here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The Ministry of Water Resources is working out a water supply
and sanitation master plan framework estimated to cost 120
million birr (about 14.5 million U.S. dollars) since last
August, the national project's coordinator Woubishet Demeke told
a workshop on logical framework of the project.
</P>
<P>
The project, due to be finished within four years, is aimed at
 promoting sustainable resources utilization in the areas of
natural resources and environmental management in the country,
Woubishet said.
</P>
<P>
According to the coordinator, the government of Netherlands
finances 81 percent of the cost of the project and Ethiopia
covers the balance.
</P>
<P>
Currently only about 26 percent of the 62-million Ethiopian
population get access to clean water, Ethiopian Water Resources
Minister Shiferaw Jarso announced at the workshop. 
</P>
</TEXT>
