<HEADLINE> Suspect Confesses to Assassination Attempt on Iranian Reformist </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, April 18 (Xinhua) -- The principal suspect in the
abortive assassination against a prominent Iranian reformist and
close ally of President Mohammad Khatami has confessed to his
crime, the Islamic Republic News Agency reported on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Iran's First Deputy Chief of the Judiciary Hadi Marvi told the
agency in Bushehr in southern Iran that he had talked personally to
the main suspect, who has explicitly confessed to the murder
attempt.
</P>
<P>
"He (the suspect) explicitly confessed to having committed the
act and said he would tell the court the same thing," Marvi said,
without giving the name of the suspect.
</P>
<P>
He said that the suspect confessed "without being under any
pressure" to the assassination attempt against the life of Saeed
Hajjarian, which he would reveal to the court.
</P>
<P>
Hajjarian, vice chairman of the Tehran Municipal Council and a
senior advisor to President Khatami, was shot and seriously wounded
in front of the council's hall in downtown Tehran on March 12.
</P>
<P>
Reports said that, Saeed Askar, a chemistry student, shot
Hajjarian and is the principal accused in the assassination case.
</P>
<P>
Hajjarian, a former deputy intelligence minister, has recovered
his consciousness following a long coma.
</P>
<P>
The assassination triggered a hot power struggle between the
powerful conservatives, who dominate most of the country's
sensitive organs, and reformists, the main supporters of the reform
programs of President Khatami.
</P>
<P>
The reformist councilor was believed to be a main architect of
the reformists' landslide victory in February's key parliamentary
polling, a result which humiliated the conservatives.
</P>
<P>
The reformists and conservatives have accused each other of
having a hand in the assassination attempt, particularly after the
arrest of another Tehran Municipal Council member Ahmad Hakimipour
on Friday in connection with the assassination attempt.
</P>
<P>
Hakimipour became a suspect in the assassination case because a
letter handed over to Hajjarian, which prepared the ground for the
assassination attempt, was signed by Hakimipour.
</P>
<P>
The conservatives urged authorities concerned to find out the
relations between the suspects and Hakimipour as well as possible
links with the serial political killings in the country during the
recent two years.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the reformists claimed that bringing Hakimipour's
letter to the assassination scene was a well-designed plot by
certain people against the reformists.
</P>
<P>
The reformist-dominated city council on Monday lodged a strong
protest against Hakimipour's arrest and said that "the agents of
threat who are known to the public are free" while Hakimipour who
rushed Hajjarian to hospital has been arrested. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
