<HEADLINE> Assad Has Strong Desire to Establish Peace: Canadian PM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAMASCUS, April 18 (Xinhua) -- Visiting Canadian Prime Minister
Jean Chretien said here Tuesday Syrian President Hafez al-Assad
wanted to carry on the Middle East peace process to the end and had
a strong desire to establish peace in the region.
</P>
<P>
Winding up his two-day visit to Syria, Chretien told reporters
at the Damascus International Airport Tuesday afternoon after his
talks with Assad that Assad briefed him on Syria's stance towards
the peace process and the talks were very good.
</P>
<P>
Asked about the dispute between Syria and Israel over Lake
Tiberias, the Canadian leader said the Syrian position was made
clear to the public and "this issue should be solved through
negotiations with Israel."
</P>
<P>
The Syrian-Israeli peace talks were snagged since January partly
due to the dispute as Israel claims full sovereignty over the lake
while Syria wants to restore its sovereignty over the northeastern
coast according to the border lines of June 4, 1967.
</P>
<P>
However, there are some proposals to launch joint tourist
projects on the coasts of the lake between the two countries or
declare it a nature reserve.
</P>
<P>
Chretien said both Canada and Syria are for Israel's withdrawal
from the Golan Heights which Israel seized from Syria in 1967 and
south Lebanon where Israel maintains an occupation zone with the
claim to protect its north.
</P>
<P>
His talks with Assad also dealt with the issues of Palestinian
refugees and Canada's participation in the Untied Nations truce-
monitoring mission in the Golan area, Chretien said.
</P>
<P>
There are 11 Canadians in the 190-strong mission.
</P>
<P>
The talks also touched on bilateral ties, especially on boosting
trade, he added.
</P>
<P>
The Syrian-Canadian trade volume stood at just 23.4 million U.S.
dollars in 1999.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on the results of his tour in the region, which had
taken him to Israel, the Palestinian self-rule areas, Egypt,
Lebanon, Jordan, Chretien said "In all my stops in the region I
found a genuine desire to establish a permanent peace and
stability."
</P>
<P>
"This reflects the common interests of all concerned parties.
Thereby, the parties should find the way for peace and we encourage
them to do so," the Canadian leader added, noting that peace was
very important for the economic and social development of the
region.
</P>
<P>
The world is heading for globalization and every country should
concentrate on investment in the fields of science and technology
in order to assume the best position in "the global village," he
pointed out. 
</P>
