<HEADLINE> Iranians Protest Cancellation of Election Results </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, April 18 (Xinhua) -- A group of residents blocked a main
road in southern Iran on Tuesday to protest the nullification of
parliamentary election results in certain constituencies by the
conservative Guardians Council (GC).
</P>
<P>
The protesters blocked the main road linking important cities of
Shiraz in Fars province and Bandar Abbas in Hormogan province,
forcing vehicles to change their way, the Islamic Republic News
Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The angry people, mainly from the Saravan Kovar and Kharameh
constituency of Fars Province, staged the protest following the GC
cancelled the election result in the constituency with no sound
reasons, the agency said.
</P>
<P>
The protestors also gathered in front of the district governor's
office and chanted slogans to voice their opposition to the
nullification of the election tally.
</P>
<P>
Eyewitnesses said the protestors also damaged some public
buildings and facilities in the provincial town of Sarvestan.
</P>
<P>
Iran has been clouded by political tension since reformers
allied to President Mohammed Khatami won an overwhelming victory in
the sixth parliamentary election in February, ending a long-time
conservative majority in the parliament.
</P>
<P>
The powerful conservatives, unwilling to accept the humiliating
defeat, have taken strong measures to counter the reformist
campaign, including summoning reformist journalists to courts and
overturning by force part of the election results.
</P>
<P>
Supreme leader Ayatollah Ali Khamenei and the elite Islamic
Revolutionary Guards have also warned against American-style
reforms in the country, even hinting that "violent" measures may be
taken to safeguard the Islamic order in the country.
</P>
<P>
As a watchdog on elections, the GC has so far announced the
invalidity of elections in a number of constituencies around the
country. In some cases, it even directly transferred the victories
of reformers to conservatives.
</P>
<P>
The measure has stirred up a series of protests recently,
including some violent ones which resulted in the arrest of scores
of people by the police.
</P>
<P>
The council on Monday also announced that the votes of six
candidates in Tehran Province will be recounted due to certain
complaints.
</P>
<P>
The six candidates ranked from the 28th to the 33rd in the first
round of election in the constituency, which has 30 seats. Former
president Hashemi Rafsanjani, supported by the conservatives,
ranked the 30th as the last winner in Tehran.
</P>
<P>
Since the election was held on February 18, the announcement of
the final results has been delayed again and again, with several
recounting of votes. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
