<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iranian Majlis Passes Hard-line Amendment to Press Law </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, April 18 (Xinhua) -- Iran's outgoing conservative Majlis
(parliament) on Tuesday passed a hard-line amendment to the press
law, imposing more restrictions on the country's freedom-seeking
press.
</P>
<P>
The newly-approved amendment sets more strict conditions for
authorities to grant licenses to publications and instructs the
Ministry of Culture and Islamic Guidance to investigate any
complaints against the press.
</P>
<P>
It also authorizes public courts, Islamic revolutionary courts
and other judicial bodies to hold open trials on press violations
with the presence of a press jury, which will be formed by 21
members in Tehran and by 14 members in the other provincial capital
cities.
</P>
<P>
The amendment, which will become a legislation only after the
approval of the conservative Guardians Council, also bans any new
publications to replace the closed ones or use the symbols or
similar frames of the closed ones, the conservative evening paper
Kayhan reported.
</P>
<P>
The approval of the outlines of the amendment last July
triggered a political disturbance with serious street clashes
between students and anti-riot police, the worst since the 1979
Islamic revolution.
</P>
<P>
Iran's moderate Minister of Culture and the Islamic Guidance
Ataollah Mohajerani said in a reaction that the amendment to the
press law contradicts the constitution of the country.
</P>
<P>
"We should wait and see, what the Guardians Council will say
when the body examines whether or not the legislation is in
conformity with the constitution," the Islamic Republic News Agency
quoted him as saying.
</P>
<P>
However, the conservative Majlis Speaker Nateq Nouri said the
amendment has removed ambiguities in the press law to some extent
and he favors the removal of all ambiguities in order to prevent
any possible conflict among related organs.
</P>
<P>
The amendment was approved amid mounting pressure on the pro-
reform newspapers and journalists, only one month before the
conservatives hand over the powerful Majlis to the reformists who
won an overwhelming victory in the February parliamentary election.
</P>
<P>
In the past one month, at least four managing directors of
reformist newspapers have been summoned to the conservative courts
and a number of journalists and writers have been interrogated.
</P>
<P>
Mohajerani said last week his ministry is determined to defend
the press freedom and will propose a bill to the new reformist
Majlis to revise the press law annulling the right of any state
organs to revoke the licenses of any newspapers.
</P>
<P>
He said the reformists will amend the press law in favor of the
media in the new parliament. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
