<HEADLINE> U.S. Authorities Urged to Rescue Cuban Boy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Speaking on the National Broadcasting Company (NBC) TV show, Dr.
Irwin Redlener said a home video about Elian released by the
relatives last week looks "exactly like we might see in a hostage
situation."
</P>
<P>
On Monday, the U.S. Immigration Naturalization Service (INS)
released a letter by Redlener, saying that Elian is now "in a
state of imminent danger to his physical and emotional well-being
in a home that I consider to be psychologically abusive."
</P>
<P>
The letter, addressed to Attorney General Janet Reno and INS
Commissioner Doris Meissner, said that the six-year-old boy was
being "horrendously exploited" and "needs to be rescued."
</P>
<P>
Redlener, professor of pediatrics at the Albert Einstein
College of Medicine in New York City, told NBC that he was
particularly disturbed by the videotape the relatives made of the
boy.
</P>
<P>
Last week, the Miami relatives defied a deadline by the
government to surrender Elian and filed an emergency asylum for
the boy to the 11th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals in Atlanta,
which has not made a ruling.
</P>
<P>
The Justice Department asked the court to lift a temporary order
that bars Elian's removal from the United States and to order
Lazaro Gonzalez to release the boy. Such a ruling could allow the
government to take immediate action.
</P>
<P>
Elian was rescued near a shipwreck in the Atlantic sea off
Florida on November 25 last year and was sent to his Miami
relatives who has been taking custody of the boy ever since then.
</P>
<P>
The INS ruled that Elian belongs to his father, Juan Miguel
Gonzalez, while the Miami relatives insist the boy should stay
with them in the United States. 
</P>
