<HEADLINE> Kuchma, Putin Discuss Gas, Partnership </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Putin, on his first overseas trip since he won the March 26
presidential elections, said the two neighboring countries should
strengthen their strategic partnership, the Interfax news agency
reported.
</P>
<P>
He said that cooperation in economy, security and the
humanitarian area was of particular importance.
</P>
<P>
The two leaders discussed cooperation in arms trading
enterprises and the joint manufacture and sales of An-70 jet
aircraft.
</P>
<P>
They also addressed ways of coordinating their short-term and
long-term energy policies and Ukraine's gas debts to Russian
natural gas giant Gazprom.
</P>
<P>
Together with penalties and interest, Ukraine now owes Gazprom
2.1 billion dollars for gas, Interfax said.
</P>
<P>
Kuchma and Putin ordered the chiefs of the intergovernmental
commission to come up with proposals before May on how to solve
bilateral problems, especially those related to the gas debt.
</P>
<P>
They also agreed to keep permanent personal contacts in an
effort to solve the outstanding issues, Kuchma told reporters
following enlarged negotiations, Interfax reported.
</P>
<P>
In addition, Kuchma pledged to take immediate and "tough
measures" to prevent the re-export of Russian gas exported to
Ukraine.
</P>
<P>
Interfax quoted Gazprom Chief Executive Rem Vyakhirev as saying
earlier that Ukraine had stolen 7.1 billion cubic meters of
Russian gas.
</P>
<P>
Following their meeting in Kiev, Kuchma and Putin flew to the
Black Sea port of Sevastopol aboard the Ukrainian president's
private aircraft.
</P>
<P>
They continued their working discussions aboard the plane
during the flight, Interfax reported, quoting Kuchma's press
secretary, Alexander Martynenko.
</P>
<P>
According to their schedule, Kuchma and Putin will lay wreaths
at the monument to the defenders of Sevastopol and board the
Ukrainian Navy cruiser "Getman Sagaidachny" and the Russian Black
Sea Fleet cruiser "Moskva."
</P>
<P>
While in Sevastopol, Putin reiterated Moscow's staunch
opposition to NATO eastward expansion that could incorporate
former Soviet republics and push its borders closer to Russia.
</P>
<P>
"Our position is dictated by our national interests," he said.
</P>
<P>
Putin, who visited Belarus and Britain prior to his arrival in
Ukraine, will leave for Moscow Tuesday evening and Kuchma will
return to Kiev, Interfax said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
