<HEADLINE> Romania to Have Most Performing Weather Survey System in Europe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUCHAREST, April 18 (Xinhua) -- Romania, in 30 months at the
latest, will benefit from one of the most performing weather
survey systems the world over, the official Rompres news agency
Tuesday quoted the Director of the National Meteorology and
Hydrology Institute Ioan Sandu as saying.
</P>
<P>
According to him, the Romanian authorities signed on Monday a
contract with the America-based Lockheed Martin Overseas
Corporation, for putting in place the National Integrated
Meteorological System.
</P>
<P>
"It's the first European country benefiting from such a system,
"Ioan Sandu said, adding that five Doppler radars in S band will
be bought as well as a radar for wind detection, 5 lightning
stations for the aviation protection, a high performance computer,
50 automated weather forecasting stations, more than 75 working
station for information viewing and 10 weather stations for
forecasts concerning the Danube and the Black Sea.
</P>
<P>
The contract is worth 55 million U.S. dollars, a loan re-
payable in 10 years, with a grace period of 30 months. "A
condition in the contract says that in the 30 months the system
has to turn operational. The loan has governmental guarantees,"
Ioan sandu added.
</P>
<P>
The buying of this equipment and its introduction into the
Integrated Meteorological System allows for the place and the
moment to be anticipated when floods, strong winds causing
disasters take place, as well as hail storms, ice, fog, thunder
storms, air turbulence, forest and technological fires, air
pollution dispersion.
</P>
<P>
"When we have this system, nobody can say any longer that
people have not been warned. The system will be the most
performing in Europe, it will be compatible with NATO's and the
World Meteorological Organization's. As a matter of fact the
system covers all the Balkans and we shall supply weather
information to Yugoslavia, Greece, Bulgaria,'' the director
concluded. 
</P>
</TEXT>
