<HEADLINE> CBI's Plan to Salvage UK Transport System </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 18 (Xinhua) - Salvaging Britain's crisis-hit
transport system will cost more than 200 billion pounds over the
next ten years, according to the Confederation of British Industry
(CBI).
</P>
<P>
The CBI's National Council, the ruling body of members,Tuesday
agreed overall transport spending proposals. It calculated its
figures by costing the measures needed to achieve the government's
best-case projections for reducing congestion over the period to
2010.
</P>
<P>
The total includes 25 billion pounds on trunk roads and
motorways, 79 billion pounds on local transport, 62 billion pounds
on rail, 9 billion pounds on aviation, 3 billion pounds on ports
and waterways, and 2 billion pounds on research into technology.
</P>
<P>
Digby Jones, CBI Director-General, said: "After years of under-
investment and delayed projects, the present transport system is
failing business and society. That is damaging to wealth creation,
social inclusion and employment."
</P>
<P>
"Now is the time for the government to turn words into action
by making tough spending and funding choices. That is the only way
to tackle the poor services, overcrowding,unacceptable congestion
and concerns about safety," he added.  
</P>
</TEXT>
