<HEADLINE> S. African Inflation Rate Rises in March </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, April 18 (Xinhua) -- South Africa's headline
inflation rate for March this year increased to 3.4 percent
year-on-year, up from February's 2. 4 percent, official statistics
released on Tuesday showed.  The increased rate -- the annual
rate of change in the Consumer Price Index (CPI) for metropolitan
areas -- was mainly due to annual increases in transport
(especially a 27.9 percent rise in the petrol price over the year)
, food, medical care and household operation, Statistics South
Africa said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
"These were partially offset by the large decrease in mortgage
interest rates over the 12-month period. The average interest rate
on home loans dropped from 21 percent to 14.5 percent in the last
12 months," the statement said.
</P>
<P>
The inflation rate for metropolitan and other areas in March
was 3.5 percent, compared to February's 2.7 percent.
</P>
<P>
The core inflation rate increased from February's eight percent
to 8.1 percent for March in metropolitan areas. This rate excludes
interest rates on mortgage bonds, overdrafts, assessment rates,
fresh and frozen meat, fish, vegetables and fruits, nuts and
changes in value added tax (VAT).
</P>
<P>
The price index for non-food items in metropolitan areas showed
an annual rate of increase of 2.5 percent for March, compared to
February's 1. 6 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000418.0042 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mugabe Pledges to Resolve land Issue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, April 18 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwean President Robert Mugabe
said on Tuesday that his government was determined to resolve the
land issue once and for all.
</P>
<P>
In his national address to mark 20 years of independence,
Mugabe said the issue of land was the last colonial question
heavily qualifying the sovereignty of the people of Zimbabwe.
</P>
<P>
He said he could understand the frustration of the war veterans
and the pressures faced by white commercial farmers which was
emanating from the unwillingness of the British government to
honor its commitment to land reform and the resistance to the land
clause in the rejected draft constitution.
</P>
<P>
"Two weeks ago I met with British Foreign Secretary who
suggested Zimbabwe sends a delegation to the United Kingdom to
re-open negotiations on land reforms," he said.
</P>
<P>
He called on Zimbabweans to desist from engaging in fist fights
because this had been called for to remove the white colonialists
which they had successfully achieved.
</P>
<P>
"We called for those with strong fists to join us in the war
and we succeeded in removing white rule, but now it is time to
take care of ourselves, to build Great Zimbabwe's collapsing walls
and to work hard in peace," he said.
</P>
<P>
Mugabe said the past 20 years had seen enormous developmental
changes that had touched practically every life with dramatic and
unmatched stride being made in education at all levels.
</P>
<P>
He said in education from 2,401 primary schools with a combined
 enrolment of 82,000, there were now over 4,500 with a combined
enrolment in excess of 2.3 million pupils while secondary schools
had grown from 177 with 66,215 pupils to 1,548 catering for over
700,000 pupils.
</P>
<P>
He said literacy levels grew from 62 percent at independence to
82 percent the best on the continent while 456 health centres, 612
rural hospitals, 25 district hospitals as well as one provincial
hospital in all eight provinces had been upgraded or built.
</P>
<P>
"Regrettably, the enormous progress we have been making over
the years have been reversed by the growing HIV/AIDS menace, but a
lot is happening by way of raising awareness," he said.
</P>
<P>
On the economy, he said more needed to be done because gains
had been both lean and erratic.
</P>
<P>
He said economic growth had been marginal and unemployment had
risen accounting for current hardships.
</P>
<P>
He added that interest and inflation rates had made life
difficult for many people while export performance had been dismal
and made worse by the depressed nature of prices of those
commodities that trade in on the international market.
</P>
<P>
To this end Mugabe said the government had initiated the
Millennium Economic Recovery Program which was seeking to
consolidate fiscal reform, accelerate public enterprise reforms,
stabilize prices at lower levels, stabilize the value of the
Zimbabwean dollar and resolve the foreign currency shortage.
</P>
<P>
He said this year's national independence celebrations had been
 cancelled because the resources that were going to be used in the
 celebrations had been channeled to assisting the victims of the
Cyclone Eline. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
