<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Africa Not to Intervene in Zimbabwe's Land Issue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, April 18 (Xinhua) -- South African Deputy
President Jacob Zuma on Tuesday shrugged off opposition calls for
a tough stance towards Zimbabwe in the wake of violence over land
issue.
</P>
<P>
He was speaking amid reports that a second Zimbabwean farmer
was shot dead on his farm by war veterans who have occupied
white-owned farms.
</P>
<P>
"I don't think we accept that matters must be resolved through
violence. We hold a view that conflicts must be resolved amicably
and peacefully," Zuma said.
</P>
<P>
South Africa will not be able to play a responsible role in the
region " if it is going to stand up whenever there is something
and condemn everybody", he said.
</P>
<P>
"We are running a country, we are running relations with
countries around us. We can't be standing and condemning everybody
when in fact you are not informed about the issues. If you do so
you are reducing the scope of your own involvement," he stressed.
</P>
<P>
Zuma added South Africa has to look at the issue more broadly
rather than just "to stand and condemn". 
</P>
</TEXT>
