<HEADLINE> Bangladesh Stresses Need for North-South Cooperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, April 18 (Xinhua) -- At the just concluded first-ever
South Summit of the G-77, Bangladesh stressed the need for North-
South cooperation and held the view that the North should help the
South "equitably share the benefits of globalization," said
Foreign Minister Abdus Samad Azad here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Briefing newsmen at the Conference Room of the Foreign Ministry,
Azad said that at the Plenary of the Summit which was held in
Havana from April 10 to 14, he presented the statement of the
Bangladeshi government, saying that globalization presents
opportunities and challenges to the countries of the South.
</P>
<P>
"Our objectives should be to regulate the forces of
globalization in a manner that will permit each country to develop
through participation," he added.
</P>
<P>
Talking about the role of the Bangladesh delegation, the
foreign minister said that as coordinator of the Least Developed
Countries (LDCs), Bangladesh was required to play an important
role in projecting the LDC interests.
</P>
<P>
According to Azad, at the initiative of Bangladesh, a very
important paragraph on the LDCs was included in the declaration,
which highlighted the eradication of poverty, equitable
implementation of the World Trade Organization Agreements, free
access to LDC exports in the world markets and debt cancellation.
</P>
<P>
Referring to the next NAM Summit to be held in Dhaka in 2001,
Azad said it would be "a historic one with the movement making a
significant leap forward in securing its position at the
international level." 
</P>
</TEXT>
