<HEADLINE> Canadian Forces to Be Cut below 60,000 People, Report Says </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, April 18 (Xinhua) -- The Canadian forces will soon be
trimmed down to 59,000 personnel, the Ottawa Citizen newspaper
reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Citing the new Department of National Defense planning document,
the newspaper said the forces will be reduced by about 1,000
people, including 28 warrant and chief warrant officers, 48
captains and majors and nine colonels and lieutenant colonels.
</P>
<P>
The number of brigadier and major generals remains at a total
of 61, with one position of lieutenant general expected to be
eliminated to reduce the number of that rank to nine, the
newspaper said.
</P>
<P>
Defense Department spokesman Navy Lieut. Ken MacKillop was
quoted as saying the drop to 59,000 is expected to be reached this
year, not in 2002 as suggested in the document.
</P>
<P>
The bottom line is that there is not enough money to modernize
and to keep the forces at the 60,000 level, which was set in the
country's 1994 defense White Paper, according to the newspaper.
</P>
<P>
The federal government announced last month that the Canadian
forces would receive 1.5 billion Canadian dollars (about 1.1
billion U.S. dollars) extra over a three-year period.
</P>
<P>
The money is in the main earmarked for upgrading and purchasing
equipment, training, quality-of-life initiatives and the
continuing cost of Kosovo, the newspaper said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
