<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Farmers Benefit From Environmental Projects (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANCHANG, April 18 (Xinhua) -- Zhu Qingneng, a farmer from east
China's Jiangxi Province, can not help laughing every time he
talks about an ecological project which has brought him a lot of
money and greatly improved the environment in his hometown.
</P>
<P>
Zhu, head of the Chang'an Horticulture Farm in Xinfeng County,
owns a 66.67-hectare orchard, a fish pond with a water area of 13.
33 hectares, and a pig farm with over 1,400 pigs.
</P>
<P>
Zhu explains that he uses the swine waste for generating
methane, and then the waste residue from the methane pits is
planted under fruit trees.
</P>
<P>
This ecological project has been expanded in an area of over 50
kilometers this year, which produces 10 million yuan (1.2 million
U.S. dollars) annually.
</P>
<P>
Yang Shidi, deputy chief of the Jiangxi Provincial Agriculture
Bureau, said that at present more than 600,000 rural families in
the province have built methane pits, saving over 200,000 hectares
of fuel forest and 88 million U.S. dollars each year.
</P>
<P>
Another project designated to comprehensively harness the
province's mountains, rivers and lakes also results in good
ecological and economic returns. Sixteen countries and
international organizations have shown great interest in the
project and have visited Jiangxi.
</P>
<P>
At present, China has more than 200 pilot counties for
implementing ecological agricultural projects, seven of them have
been called "Global Top 500" by the United Nations Environment
Program.
</P>
<P>
China now has 49 million hectares of arable land suffering from
soil erosion, accounting for 38 percent of the country's total, 10
million hectares of polluted farm land which has reduced grain
output by 10 billion kilograms and caused economic losses of 12.5
billion yuan (about 1.5 billion U.S. dollars) annually. (
more)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000418.0060 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> McDonald's to Open Branch in China's Most Populous Province </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ZHENGZHOU, April 18 (Xinhua) -- US fast food giant McDonald's
has signed a contract with the Zhengzhou Friendship Commercial
Group Corp. worth five million U.S. dollars during the just-ended
Henan trade fair, planning to set up over 30 Mcdonald's
restaurants in China's most populous province.
</P>
<P>
Herbert Wong, purchasing director with McDonald's (China) Co.
Ltd., said though there is an economic gap between Henan and the
eastern provinces. They are substantial economic returns in the
business expansion in the province. The first McDonald's
restaurant in Zhengzhou is expected to open in July.
</P>
<P>
McDonald's has opened 25,000 restaurants in 119 countries and
regions since the first restaurant opened in the United States in
1955. There are 257 McDonald's restaurants in 17 provinces and
municipalities in China.
</P>
<P>
Liu Jichen, president of the Zhengzhou Friendship Commercial (
Group) Corp., said he hopes that cooperation with McDonald's will
bring mutual benefit to both parties. The Group has so far opened
over 30 department stores in Zhengzhou.
</P>
<P>
Henan has a population of some 93 million. Its GDP was 456.5
billion yuan (about 54.78 billion U.S. dollars) last year, ranking
fifth in China. 
</P>
</TEXT>
