<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Farmers Benefit From Environmental Projects (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
As early as 1984, the State Council made a decision to develop
ecological agriculture in China. In 1999, the State Council vowed
to put an end to the deteriorating ecological system within 50
years.
</P>
<P>
China plans to expand the ecological pilot zones to many cities
and counties in the next decade.
</P>
<P>
Chen Yaobang, minister of agriculture, said that to support the
development of the country's western region, his ministry will
select one or two counties from each province in the western
region for implementing ecological agricultural projects.
</P>
<P>
During the Tenth Five-Year Plan (2001-2005) period, the
Ministry of Agriculture will launch a program in 150 counties in
the western region.
</P>
<P>
Many other provinces in China have joined in the efforts to
develop ecological agriculture. Hainan, the country's largest
special economic zone, announced recently that it will turn itself
into an ecological agricultural giant in China.
</P>
<P>
Experts noted that ecological agriculture plays a very
important role in reforming China's traditional agriculture and
speed up China's access into the WTO.
</P>
<P>
Given that organic food products are popular in developed
countries and the coastal areas of the country, the province is
spending more efforts in developing ecological agriculture and
some 100 varieties of organic food products.
</P>
<P>
The Dazhangshan Mountain organic tea produced in Maoyuan County
has accounted for 60 percent of the organic tea market in the
European Union, earning 2.5 million U.S. dollars in foreign
exchange annually.  
</P>
</TEXT>
