<HEADLINE> U.S. Insurer Praises China's New Regulations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 18 (Xinhua) -- China has made progress in its
regulatory system of the insurance industry by issuing new
regulations on branches of foreign insurers in China, said Ian
Lancaster, senior Vice President of Chubb Group of Insurance
Companies.
</P>
<P>
He said at a press conference at Chubb's Beijing office today
that the new regulations conform with international practices.
This demonstrates that China is introducing laws and regulations
according to the agreement that the United States and China
reached on China's accession to the World Trade Organization (WTO).
</P>
<P>
As the executive vice president of the U.S. Chamber of Commerce
in China, Lancaster flew to Washington with other U.S. businessmen
to lobby for granting China normal trade relations last week. "I
am very optimistic about that China will live up to its
obligations under the WTO," said Lancaster.
</P>
<P>
He said that China's accession to the WTO will have a win-win
outcome for both the U.S. and China. He also gave high marks to
the China Insurance Regulatory Commission (CIRC) and other
relevant authorities for introducing international-standard laws
and regulations and building an insurance industry in accordance
with international practice.
</P>
<P>
According to Lancaster, the CIRC has already approved Federal
Insurance Co., a subsidiary of Chubb, to set up its China General
Representative Office in Shanghai. Lancaster will be in charge of
the Office.  
</P>
