<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Play More Important Role in Global Economy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 18 (Xinhua)-- China is going to play a more
important role in the world economy with a total purchase plan of
over two trillion US dollars in the next ten years, said Li
Rongrong, vice minister of the State Economic and Trade Commission,
here today.
</P>
<P>
"China's development cannot proceed without interaction with
the rest of the world. China's contributions will also improve
global prosperity," Li said, adding that "In line with the
globalization of the world economy and China's pending ascension
to WTO, China will be integrated into the global economy in a
broader sphere and a high level."
</P>
<P>
China's foreign trade has risen to 35 percent compared to
twenty years ago. Last year, China's foreign trade volume ranked
ninth in the world. China has also become the second largest
foreign capital user after the United States.
</P>
<P>
"Any company cannot call itself a multinational without a major
move or act in China," said Colette Mathur, director of the World
Economic Forum, adding that China's volume of world trade is 3.5
percent and is expected to increase to seven percent in five years
after joining WTO.
</P>
<P>
Almost all participants at the China Business Summit, which
ended today, are optimistic about the imminent WTO membership for
China.
</P>
<P>
Endymion Wilkinson, head of the European Union Delegation to
China, said that China's negotiation with EU on the WTO will bring
fruitful results.
</P>
<P>
Zhang Ruimin, president of Haier Group, said that participating
in global trade is a necessity for the survival of any Chinese
company in the future.
</P>
<P>
Liu Minkang, president of the Bank of China, concluded that the
process of globalization will not waver to any personal will and
that China should find its own way into the global economy.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
