<DOCNO> XIE20000418.0065 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NASDAQ Official Says Fluctuations Normal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 18 (Xinhua) -- An NASDAQ official said here
today that recent NASDAQ Index fluctuations are normal and that it
doesn't mean bubble blowing for new and high technological shares.
</P>
<P>
Harry H. Huang, NASDAQ chief representative to China, told a
news conference on international fund-polling that the NASDAQ
Index had dropped by 25 percent last week, compared with last year
's 85.6 percent increase.
</P>
<P>
He attributed NASDAQ's development mainly to its adaptation to
new economies and its new criteria and policies for new economies
to be listed on stock markets.
</P>
<P>
"Whether it goes up or down, we call it a normal process,"
Huang said. On Monday, the NASDAQ Index began to bounce back, up 6.
6 percent.
</P>
<P>
"Our predicted index bottom line is around 3,200 points, and by
year end, it will probably climb to 4,000 or 4,300 points," he
said.
</P>
<P>
Huang said he couldn't see any impact of NASDAQ Index drops on
businesses. If any, it would be man-made factors that have nothing
to do with market.
</P>
<P>
He confirmed that the NASDAQ Stock Market, Inc. will be listed,
aiming to poll more fund to build up the NASDAQ global market
network.
</P>
<P>
Any enterprise that is listed on U.S. stock markets only covers
one third of global economic activities. NASDAQ opened NASDAQ
Japan, Hong Kong, and Europe to link world markets for the benefit
of listed companies, investment banks and investors, he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
