<HEADLINE> Vice-premier Speaks Highly of Civility Project </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 18 (Xinhua) -- Beijing Municipal departments
today donated 105 computers to middle and primary schools in rural
areas outside of Beijing for computer classes as part of a
civility project.
</P>
<P>
Vice-premier Li Lanqing has written a letter to Beijing, in
which he spoke highly of the city's effort.
</P>
<P>
Computer education in middle and primary schools is very
important at a time when the hi-tech industry is developing
rapidly, he said.
</P>
<P>
"It is not practical to wholly rely on the state to provide
computers for schools as China has a huge number of students.
Members of society can also donate computers to rural areas," the
vice-premier said, calling on other localities to do the same as
Beijing.
</P>
<P>
The project was advocated by Li himself, and met with positive
response across the country. Beijing has received more than 2,000
donated computers for 17 computer classes it has set up. 
