<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Senior Tibetan Legislator Meets U.S. Guests </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LHASA, April 18 (Xinhua) -- Thanks to democratic reforms and
the elimination of serfdom in Tibet four decades ago, this vast
autonomous region with a total area of 1.2 million square
kilometers has witnessed profound changes.
</P>
<P>
Puqung, vice chairman of the Tibet Autonomous Regional People's
Congress Standing Committee, made the remarks today in his meeting
with senior aids of U.S. Congressmen led by U.S.-based Asia
Foundation President Richard Quick.
</P>
<P>
Puqung said that the elimination of feudal serfdom in Tibet
liberated 95 percent of the serfs, including Puqung himself, who
suffered a lot from cruel exploitation and oppression
</P>
<P>
Under China's Constitution and other laws, the Law on Regional
Autonomy for China's Minority Nationalities in particular, Tibetan
people now enjoy a life of national unity.
</P>
<P>
Of 30,000 deputies at township, county and regional levels, 90
percent are Tibetan, Puqung said, adding that 13 out of 15
chairman and vice chairpersons of the regional People's Congress
Standing Committee are Tibetan, including woman living Buddha
Samding Dojepamo and living Buddha Yingzhung Gawa.
</P>
<P>
Puqung also briefed the guests on Tibet's economic achievements.
"Agriculture and animal husbandry recorded bumper harvests for 12
successive years. Grain output hit 920,000 tons, almost sufficient
for the whole region. Per-capita annual net income of farmers and
herdsmen reached 1,257 yuan and disposable income of urban
household totaled more than 5,000 yuan," he said.
</P>
<P>
Puqung also answered questions from the guests on Tibetan
ethnic and religious culture.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. visitors arrived in Lhasa Monday to start their four-
day China trip. They will tour a number of Tibetan lamaseries,
factories and museums.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
