<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Intellectual Property Evaluation in China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 18 (Xinhua) -- A senior Chinese intellectual
property (IP) official said today that evaluation IP mechanism
will push forward the commercialization of IP.
</P>
<P>
The IP evaluation has merged and developed with the development
of market economy, said Hu Zuochao, director of Coordination and
Management Department of the State Intellectual Property Office (
SIPO).
</P>
<P>
China started to carry out intangible assets evaluations on IP
in 1989. The first intangible assets evaluation office and IP
government regulations started in Shenzhen, Guangdong Province.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that China has almost a dozen professional
intangible assets evaluation offices. Meanwhile, 3,800 non-
professional ones are involved in the evaluation work, with 62,000
employees and 14,000 registered evaluators.
</P>
<P>
The state should try to clarify the distinction between the
intangible assets evaluation and the tangible assets evaluation
and standardize it with certain regulations.
</P>
<P>
Since China's adoption of the Patent Law in 1985, nationwide
patent offices have received more than one million patent
applications.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000418.0074 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Economy Improving, But Domestic Demand Still Weak: Lawmakers (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 18 (Xinhua) -- The Financial and Economic
Committee of the National People's Congress said today that the
Chinese economy is showing obvious signs of improving in the first
quarter this year, but the problem of insufficient domestic demand
remains.
</P>
<P>
Officials from the State Development and Planning Commission,
State Economic and Trade Commission, Finance Ministry, the central
bank and the State Statistics Bureau have reported on China's
current economic situation to the Committee.
</P>
<P>
In the first quarter this year, gross domestic product growth
reached 8.1 percent compared with the same period last year, and
industries achieved added value totaling 501.2 billion yuan (60.4
billion dollars), up 10.7 percent.
</P>
<P>
China's fixed asset investment surged a year-on-year by 8.5
percent to 223.5 billion yuan (27 billion US dollars), and 123.5
billion yuan has gone to infrastructure projects. Some 37.7
billion yuan has been directed to technical upgrading, a 12.6
percent increase.
</P>
<P>
China's foreign trade increased with import up 39.1 and exports
up by 41 percent.
</P>
<P>
In a news release, the NPC committee said these positive
economic signs have paved the way for the realization of a 7
percent economic growth in 2000.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000418.0075 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Economy Improving, Domestic Demand Still Weak: Lawmakers (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
However, there are still problems, the committee members said.
For example, the 8.5 percent growth of fixed asset investment in
the first three months was far from adequate to meet the ten
percent goal for 2000.
</P>
<P>
Currency issue was down by 1.7 percent, which will curb the
growth of market demand this year. Production capacity in some
sectors still greatly exceeds market demand.
</P>
<P>
The members held that the role of treasury bonds will stimulate
fixed asset investments.
</P>
<P>
Neglect of agriculture development should be avoided to sustain
the production of grain. Problems relating to laid-off workers
from state-owned enterprises, pensioners and rural residents
should be effectively addressed to ensure social stability,
according to the lawmakers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
