<HEADLINE> Ugandan Top Rebel Commanders Surrender to Government </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, April 18 (Xinhua) -- Two top commanders of the Allied
Democratic Forces (ADF), a rebel group fighting the Ugandan
government in the western part of the country, have surrendered to
the government.
</P>
<P>
The two commanders, ADF Chief of Staff Commander Benz and
Director of Training Rwigyema Junior, surrendered two days ago
with their six escorts and family members, according to military
spokesman Shaban Bantariza.
</P>
<P>
He told Xinhua on Tuesday that these people are free to choose
their destiny.
</P>
<P>
"They can join the government army," he said. "And they can
also choose a life style of a different nature."
</P>
<P>
"The recently passed Amnesty Law guarantees their safety and
their right to reintegration into the society," the spokesman
said.
</P>
<P>
As a result of increasing attacks against the ADF rebels active
in western Uganda, the rebels' number has dropped to about 100,
Bantariza said.
</P>
<P>
He said the Ugandan government troops have destroyed a total of
33 rebel camps in the eastern part of the Democratic Republic of
the Congo from where they launched their attacks.
</P>
<P>
The ADF rebels have often come to Uganda to abduct, kill and
maim people since January 1996. Tens of thousands of people,
including some security personnel, have been displaced due to
rampant rebel activities.
</P>
<P>
Chief of Staff of Ugandan forces James Kazini is currently
based in the western district of Kasese, spearheading the
government's efforts against ADF incursions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
