<HEADLINE> Angola Calls for Further Sanctions Against Savimbi </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, April 18 (Xinhua) -- The Angolan foreign ministry has
called for the urgent reinforcement of the sanctions against the
Angolan rebels led by Jonas Savimbi, official news agency Angop
reported here on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The ministry urged the member countries of the United Nations
Security Council to agree on the urgent enforcement of the
recommendations contained in a report put forward by the U.N.
Angola Sanctions Committee against Angolan rebels, according to
Angop.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. Security Council is currently meeting in New York to
analyze the "Angola dossier", especially the proposals contained
in the report submitted by Robert Fowler, head of the U.N.
Sanctions Committee.
</P>
<P>
"We would like the application of these recommendations to be
immediate, that is, without dictating the U.N. security council's
will nor the interests defended by the international community,"
said spokesman for Angolan foreign ministry Joao Pedro.
</P>
<P>
The report, signed up by Robert Fowler, contains 39
recommendations, essentially based on the enforcement of the
resolutions that have been passed since 1993, including the
registration of arms traders.
</P>
<P>
Of the bulk of recommendations, stress goes for the punishment
on U.N. resolution violators and the creation of mechanisms of
control, though it is not yet clear where the funds will come
from.
</P>
<P>
Savimbi's organization has been since September 1993 under a
package of sanctions that include a visa ban on his aides and
respective relatives, closure of the organizations bureaus and so
on. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
