<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fraud Costs S. Africa 6.2 Billion U.S. Dollars Annually </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, April 18 (Xinhua) -- Fraud costs South Africa 40
billion rand (about 6.2 billion U.S. dollars) every year, the
Durban Chamber of Commerce and Industry said on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The amount equals the household income of more than 100,000
South African middle-class families every year.
</P>
<P>
The chamber Monday joined forces with Tip-Offs Anonymous, which
was launched last June and is now providing a 24-hour fraud and
crime reporting subscriber service where subscribers can report
workplace dishonesty in a bid to reduce the prevalence of fraud.
</P>
<P>
The eradication of fraud is expected to boost profits of
business by at least 20 percent and greater profits will encourage
the private sector to invest elsewhere such as in education and
training, the chamber said.
</P>
<P>
A reduction in fraud can also lead to reductions in rates and
taxes and the lowering of service charges for water and
electricity. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
