<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NATO Agrees to Protect Macedonia's Border With Kosovo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIRANA, April 18 (Xinhua) -- NATO has promised to pay special
attention to the security situation on Macedonia's border with the
troubled Yugoslav province of Kosovo, and to guarantee the normal
operation of crossings along the border, it was reported here on
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
British Air Marshal Toni Stabels, the new commander of the NATO
peacekeeping force in Macedonia, made the promise to Macedonian
Prime Minister Ljupco Georgievski during a meeting in Macedonia's
capital Skopje on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Stabels' promise was a response to Macedonia's earlier requests
for the United States and the NATO-led KFOR peacekeeping force in
Kosovo to strengthen petrol on its border with Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
The Stabels-led NATO contingent in the former Yugoslav republic
is part of the KFOR, which uses Macedonia as a vital logistical
base for its operations in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
Tension has been mounting on the Macedonia-Kosovo border
following the abduction of four Macedonian soldiers on the border
early this month by a group of armed men believed to be Kosovo's
ethnic Albanian extremists. The four were later freed.
</P>
<P>
The incident prompted the Macedonian authorities to call on the
United States and NATO to beef up military strength in border
areas. Last Friday, Macedonian President Boris Trajkovski repeated
the request in a telephone conversation with U.S. Secretary of
State Madeleine Albright.
</P>
<P>
During the conversation, Trajkovski expressed grave concern
over tensions on the border, and asked Washington to deliver a
warning to various political forces in Kosovo against any
encroachment upon Macedonia's sovereignty and territorial
integrity.
</P>
<P>
He also asked Washington and the KFOR to step up patrol and
control along the border, where security is responsibility of the
U.S. contingent of the KFOR.
</P>
<P>
Macedonia has a large ethnic Albanian minority and fears that
the separatist violence that erupted last year in Kosovo could
spill over its border.
</P>
<P>
Stabels also discussed with Georgievski KFOR's relations with
Macedonia, which were tainted last Tuesday when some 30 allegedly
drunken U.S. troops were detained for involvement in a street
fight with Macedonian civilians in Skopje. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
