<DOCNO> XIE20000418.0085 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Places Importance on Asia-Europe Summit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, April 18 (Xinhua) -- The European Commission said
Tuesday that the third Asia-Europe Meeting (ASEM) will be of
special importance in setting a path for the development of
political, economic and cultural relations between the two regions
in the first decade of the new millennium.
</P>
<P>
Releasing a document addressing future perspectives and
priorities in the ASEM process, the executive body of the European
Union (EU) said its proposal for priorities in ASEM includes an
enhanced dialogue between Asia and the EU on regional and global
security issues, a stronger results-orientated cooperation on
trade and economic issues, and a dialogue on social policy issues.
</P>
<P>
The proposal also covers intensified educational exchanges,
cooperation in the field of consumer protection, and a possible
enlargement of participation in the ASEM process.
</P>
<P>
"The summit comes at a time when Asia is well on the way to
recovery from the crisis of 1997-98, and when the region's
economic and political importance for the EU has never been
greater," Chris Patten, EU Commissioner for external relations,
said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
"In the EU, we are preparing for enlargement and taking on new
responsibilities in the field of foreign policy and security based
on an increasingly strong economy and the successful establishment
of the euro and an open single market. And more than ever before,
Asia and Europe have a common interest in working together as
equal partners to meet the common challenges we face in an
increasingly inter-dependent world," Patten said.
</P>
<P>
The EU executive's working document confirms that ASEM's
advantage lies in its informal character, its multi-dimensionality
and its foundation of equal partnership between the two regions.
</P>
<P>
The third ASEM summit will be held in Seoul, South Korea, on
October 20-21, with the participation of European Commission
President Romano Prodi, heads of the 15 EU member states, and 10
Asian countries -- Brunei, China, Indonesia, Japan, South Korea,
Malaysia, the Philippines, Thailand, Singapore and Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
The first ASEM summit was held in Bangkok in 1996 and a second
in London in April 1998. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
