<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Euro Zone Inflation Up to 2.1 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, April 18 (Xinhua) -- The euro zone's annual inflation
rate rose to 2.1 percent in March from 2.0 percent in February,
the European Union (EU) statistics office, Eurostat, said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The annual inflation in the euro zone was 1.0 percent a year
earlier.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, inflation remained stable at 1.9 percent in March in
the EU. It was an average 1.2 percent in March 1999 in all 15 EU
member states.
</P>
<P>
According to the Eurostat report, highest annual inflation
rates were in Ireland with 5 percent, Finland with 3.2 percent,
Denmark, Spain and Luxembourg with 3.0 percent. The lowest rates
were in Britain with 0.7 percent, Portugal and Sweden both with 1.
4 percent.
</P>
<P>
Compared to February 2000, the annual inflation rate rose in
nine EU member states, fell in two, and remained unchanged in four.
Compared with March 1999, the biggest relative rises were in
Austria (0.2 percent to 2.0 percent) and Luxembourg (0.6 percent
to 3.0 percent), while the biggest relative falls were in Britain
(1.2 percent to 0.7 percent) and Portugal (2.8 percent to 1.4
percent).
</P>
<P>
The Eurostat also said the lowest 12-month averages up to March
were in Sweden with 0.8 percent, France with 0.9 percent, Austria
with 0.9 percent, while the highest were in Ireland with 3.1
percent, Spain with 2.5 percent and Denmark with 2.4 percent.
</P>
<P>
The 15-nation EU includes the 11-country euro zone. The euro
zone covers Belgium, Germany, Spain, France, Ireland, Italy,
Luxembourg, Netherlands, Austria, Portugal and Finland. Denmark,
Greece, Sweden and Britain are still outside the single currency
group. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
