<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, April 18 (Xinhua) -- The following are economic briefs
from the Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
BEIRUT -- Lebanon's budget deficit in March hit 340 billion
Lebanon pounds (about 226 million U.S. dollars), accounting for
about 46 percent of the total public spending, up by 103.59 percent
from 167 billion pounds (about 111 million dollars) in March l999.
</P>
<P>
Combined deficit of the budget and the treasury jumped to 56
percent of the total expenditure in the first three months this
year compared with 43 percent during the same period of last year.
</P>
<P>
A tax revenue growth is expected in the coming months with a
view that the monthly spending should not surpass the budget.
</P>
<P>
TUNIS -- Forty percent of the works of a gas pipeline for
transferring natural gas from Nabil, about 70 kilometers south of
capital Tunis, to the industrial and residential zones in Tunis
have been completed.
</P>
<P>
The project is aimed to supply the capital with natural gas from
an already-agreed-upon 5-percent quota in the Algeria-Italy gas
pipeline which passes by the Tunisian territory in Nabil province.
</P>
<P>
The 45-kilometer pipeline, launched with an investment of 29
million dinars (22.3 million U.S. dollars) in March 2000, is
expected to be completed by 2001.
</P>
<P>
MUSCAT -- Oman's sixth five-year plan (2001-2005) is based
mainly on adopting sustainable financial policies to keep the
balance between earnings and spendings with high and achievable
growth rates in terms of investments and productivity in various
fields.
</P>
<P>
It also involves employing natives, accelerating localization,
stabilizing prices, developing proper monetary and financial
policies to avoid inflationary pressures, encouraging investments
and private sector's role in developing national economy, drafting
a clear and accurate program for natural gas-oriented industries,
promoting tourism, agriculture, fishery and upgrading financial
service.
</P>
<P>
BEIRUT -- Sluggish performance characterized Lebanon's
construction sector over the first quarter of this year, showing a
crisis in real estate since the peace process on the Syrian-Israeli
track hit a snag in 1996.
</P>
<P>
The figures issued by the Lebanese Engineer Syndicate showed
that the land licensed for building during the January-April period
this year dropped by about 55 percent to 613,912 square meters
against 1,360,708 square meters in the same quarter last year.
</P>
<P>
RIYADH -- The number of Internet users in Saudi Arabia surged by
160 percent since the service was introduced to the kingdom last
year, thus making the kingdom among the top five Arab countries in
terms of Internet growth.
</P>
<P>
RIYADH -- About 7.2 million foreigners are working in Saudi
Arabia, accounting for 47 percent of the total population at
present.
</P>
<P>
The Saudi government is trying to replace the foreign labor with
native employees to rein in the rising unemployment rate among the
Saudi nationals. 
</P>
</TEXT>
