<HEADLINE> Tourists Visiting Angkor Wat of Cambodia Doubled </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PHNOM PENH, April 18 (Xinhua) -- The number of tourists
visiting Angkor Wat, Cambodia's only World Heritage site, has
doubled from about 400 people daily to about 800, the Cambodia
Daily reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The sharp increase of tourists is due to the government's 'open
skies' policy which was announced by Prime Minister Hun Sen last
December.
</P>
<P>
Some foreign airlines have already taken the advantage of the
policy and introduced direct flights to Siem Reap where Angkor Wat
is located. Besides Royal Air Cambodge, other airlines serving
Siem Reap include Vietnam Airlines and Bangkok Airways.
</P>
<P>
Bangkok Airways operate five daily flights to Siem Reap from
Bangkok, and it also started flights between Pattaya, Phuket and
Siem Reap.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Shanghai and Singapore Airlines are also considering
direct flights.
</P>
<P>
Officials expect that daily visitors to Angkor Wat could reach
1,000 once the roads to Siem Reap from Poipet and Phnom Penh are
upgraded.
</P>
<P>
With the booming of the tourism, the hotel business is strong.
The area now offers 1,520 rooms in five hotels and various guest
houses. 
</P>
</TEXT>
