<HEADLINE> Australian Stocks Close Higher </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, April 18 (Xinhua) -- The Australian sharemarket
bounced back with a two percent rise Tuesday after it was revived
by another record performance on Wall Street.
</P>
<P>
News Corp, Telstra, the big four banks and resources stocks
such as BHP and Woodside Petroleum all made strong gains.
</P>
<P>
The S&AMP;P/ASX200 index closed 66.4 points higher to 3,010.3.
</P>
<P>
News Corp, which suffered a 14 percent fall Monday, made up a
little ground Tuesday, Its ordinary shares closed up 46.6 cents
higher, or 2.6 percent, to 18.216 Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
Other media stocks also regained ground, Publishing &AMP;
Broadcasting was up 88.4 cents to 12.55 Australian dollars,
Fairfax climbed 26 cents to 5.21 Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
Technology stocks picked themselves up off the canvas after
Monday's pummeling. Solution 6 was 25 cents higher to 5.89
Australian dollars, Sausage Software added 29 cents to 3.35
Australian dollars and Ecorp crept ahead 8.3 cents to 3.033
Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
The National Australia Bank ended up 52 cents to 23.40
Australian dollars, the Commonwealth was 97.9 cents higher to 25.
874 Australian dollars, Westpac climbed 15 cents to 10.80 and ANZ
pushed up seven cents to 11.47 Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
In the telecommunications sector, Telstra gained 23 cents to 7.
35 Australian dollars, Optus was up four cents to 5.40 Australian
dollars.
</P>
<P>
In the resources sector, BHP was 30 cents higher to 17.60
Australian dollars, Woodside Petroleum was up 57 cents to 10.27
Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
National turnover was 960.3 million shares traded worth 1.96
billion Australian dollars (646.64 million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
There were 125 rising stocks, 550 falling and 442 were steady.
</P>
</TEXT>
