<DOCNO> XIE20000418.0145 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Becomes China's Largest Export Destination </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, April 18 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. replaced Japan as
China's largest export destination last year, a Chinese foreign
trade official said here at the ongoing China Export Commodity
Fair.
</P>
<P>
Chen Xinhua, vice minister of Foreign Trade and Economic
Cooperation, said at the U.S. Retail Industry and China
Enterprises Summit held during the fair today, that foreign trade
between America, the most powerful developed country, and China,
the largest developing country, is mutually complementary.
</P>
<P>
Sino-American foreign trade amounted to 61.5 billion US dollars
in 1999, up 12 percent over the previous year, according to
statistics from the General Administration of Customs. Of this
total, China's export to the US increased by 7.5 percent last year
to 42 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Chen said that exports to the U.S. are mainly light textile
products and home appliances, comparatively cheap commodities.
China also imports large amounts of high-tech products from
America, such as telecommunications and electronic gadgets and
equipment, making China the third largest importer of US goods.
</P>
<P>
The official noted that the agreement reached between China and
the U.S. in November last year on China's accession to the World
Trade Organization was consistent with the interests of people in
both countries.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
