<DOCNO> XIE20000418.0156 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mortality Rate in China Declines: Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 18 (Xinhua) -- The mortality rate of the people
of China declined last year, while the death rate for males and
people in rural areas remained higher than that for females and
people in cities, according to the latest statistics from the
Ministry of Health.
</P>
<P>
Mortality rates of urban and rural residents hit 5.88 per 1,000
people and 6.06 per 1,000 people, respectively, in 1999, compared
with 6.16 per 1,000 and 6.20 per 1,000 in 1998.
</P>
<P>
Death rates of residents in major cities and prosperous rural
areas were still higher than those in small and medium-sized
cities and underdeveloped rural regions, said the report.
</P>
<P>
Urban residents now make up 31 percent of China's population,
which was reported as 1.259 billion people at the end of last year.
</P>
<P>
People who died at the age of 65 and above accounted for about
60 percent in rural areas and 70 percent in cities. However,
mortality rate for rural children was significantly higher than
that in cities.
</P>
<P>
The birth rate for China in 1999 was 15.23 per 1,000 people,
according to the State Statistics Bureau.  
</P>
</TEXT>
