<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israel to Free 13 Lebanese, Keep 2 Eminent Guerrillas </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, April 18 (Xinhua) -- Israeli security cabinet Tuesday
agreed unanimously to respect the Supreme Court ruling regarding
the release of 13 Lebanese detainees now in custody in Israel
</P>
<P>
The inner-circle policy-making panel pledged it will carry out
the ruling by Wednesday afternoon, said a communique issued Tuesday
morning after its special session.
</P>
<P>
The decision finally cleared the way for the transfer of these
detainees to the International Red Cross Organization in south
Lebanon, which is originally set to take place on Monday.
</P>
<P>
However, two most prominent detainees Sheik Abdel Karim Obeid
and Mustafa Dirani, will still be held in Israeli prison for at
least a month.
</P>
<P>
The security cabinet communique stated that the government will
make a special effort to guarantee the continued detainment in
Israel of Dirani and Obeid.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Tel Aviv District Court, which is handling the
urgent appeal by the state to extend the detention of the two,
adjourned hearing on Tuesday morning.
</P>
<P>
According to the court, the hearing is scheduled to resume on
May 8, so the two will be kept in Israeli custody at least until
that time.
</P>
<P>
All these detainees had been illegally kept for years in Israeli
prison as bargaining chips for the information or return of missing
Israeli soldiers, including Israel Air Force Navigator Ron Arad,
who has been missing in Lebanon since 14 years ago.
</P>
<P>
The so-called administrative detention without trial faced legal
challenges after the Supreme Court ruled Wednesday that eight of
the Lebanese detainees should be released, as they are not posing
security threats to Israel.
</P>
<P>
As the principle of this ruling could arguably be applied to
other seven Lebanese hostages, the prison authority announced later
that five of the remaining prisoners will also be set free, except
Dirani and Obeid.
</P>
<P>
Obeid, a spiritual leader of Lebanese Hezbollah guerrillas,was
kidnapped from his home in south Lebanon in 1989, and Dirani,
security chief of the Lebanese resistance militia Amal, was
captured by Israeli agents in a special operation in 1994.
</P>
<P>
It was Dirani who held Arad after the Israeli navigator
parachuted from his hit Phantom fighter on Lebanese soils in
October 1986. Dirani reportedly traded Arad to either Hezbollah or
its supporter Iran later.
</P>
<P>
The government attorney in their cases argued that the two do
pose a threat to Israel's security, a move aimed at seeking a new
pretext to justify their continued incarceration.
</P>
<P>
The Supreme Court ruling had prompted some senior members of the
defense and judicial establishment to explore possible legal ways
to circumvent the decision, as the court had rejected a last-minute
appeal against the release of the 13 detainees on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The security cabinet session on Tuesday decided to begin an
immediate legislative process to examine and permit the holding of
enemy fighters in accordance with the concept in international law.
</P>
<P>
The proposed legislation, according to the communique, would
shift the decision on detention from the courts to the defense
minister.
</P>
<P>
It would hold these detainees, such as members of Lebanese
Hezbollah guerrillas who are fighting to end Israeli occupation in
south Lebanon, by methods other than administrative detention.
</P>
<P>
The security cabinet said it will bring such a draft bill in
fast track before the Knesset (Parliament), which is due to break
the current recess for the Jewish Passover Holiday and convene in
special session on Tuesday or Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
It also promised to continue making maximum efforts to obtain
information regarding Israel's prisoner of wars and servicemen
missing in action, in order to secure their return to Israel.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000418.0159 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mekong Countries Agree on Commercial Navigation Pact </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
A press release of The Thai Ministry of Foreign Affairs was
quoted as saying that Thai Transport and Communications Minister
Suthep Thuegsuban will sign the agreement with his Chinese, Lao,
and Myanmese counterparts on April 20 in Ta Khi Lek province of
Myanmar.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement, the four countries could launch commercial
navigation free of charge between the Chinese town of Zhi Mao to
Luang Phrabang province of Laos, and commercial vessels of all the
four countries would be equally granted privileges on customs
procedures, as well as on the use of port and warehouse facilities,
it said.
</P>
<P>
The accord, which would take effect one year after the signing
of the signatory countries, was part of a cooperative framework
under a growth quadrangle in the sub-region, it stated.
</P>
<P>
In the meantime before the agreement will take effect, the four
signatory countries will jointly work out for common navigation
rules,covering traffic and safety regulations, as well as
standards of vessels and their internal equipment, crew documents,
procedures of ports'entry and exit, rescue operations, and
insurances, It added.
</P>
<P>
Suthep would also hold an informal meeting with his Lao,
Chinese,and Myanmese counterparts after the signing ceremony of
the agreement to discuss cooperation on transport and
communication projects, it said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
