<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysia's Economy on Mend: Researcher </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, April 18 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia's economy is
definitely on the mend, Malaysian Institute of Economic Research (
MIER) Executive Director Mohamed Ariff said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The MIER is sticking to the six percent real gross domestic
product(GDP) growth this year it forecasted last January for the
country, he said at a press briefing held for the release of the
economic think- tank's "Malaysian Economic Outlook: 2000 which
contains its quarterly projection.
</P>
<P>
Growth this year would be private sector-driven with the public
sector taking secondary role, he said, adding the GDP could expand
up to 6.5 percent but beyond that, it would overheat.
</P>
<P>
Malaysia's economy, which contracted 7.5 percent in 1998, grew
by 5.4 percent in 1999.
</P>
<P>
Noting improved consumer confidence, he said consumers tend to
spend more than previously while many household reported higher
wages and employment opportunities.
</P>
<P>
He said although 70 percent of the 1,250 household surveyed
expected inflationary pressure in the future, consumers were less
concerned about inflation compared with the previous quarter.
</P>
<P>
The forecasted 3.4 percent inflation this year "is a non issue
but we should not take it for granted," he said.
</P>
<P>
The MIER's survey of some 600 manufacturing companies in the
first quarter of this year showed businesses remained upbeat over
the economy, Ariff said, adding a large number of manufacturers
were getting higher export orders and sales while the number of
those with low production and sales declined.
</P>
<P>
He predicted that the next year's GDP growth would be a bit
lower than the 6.0 percent projected for 2000 as some correction
in the U.S.economy were expected. 
</P>
</TEXT>
