<HEADLINE> Angola Considers Explosion in Lisbon's Discotheque "Grave and Worrying" </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, April 18 (Xinhua) -- Angolan government considered
"very grave and worrying" the incident of gas explosion in a
discotheque located in the downtown Lisbon that killed five
Angolan citizens and two from Spain and Portugal, according to the
spokesman of the Angolan foreign ministry.
</P>
<P>
Joao Pedro said that the Angolan government is expecting for
official information from the Portuguese authorities on the bandit
action, which took place at the dawn of last Sunday in the
downtown Lisbon.
</P>
<P>
As the motive of the incident has not been made clear, the
Angolan government can not attribute the responsibility to
anybody, said the official source.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that the victims got smashed by the iron bars
located on the entrances or got poisoned by the gas launched when
some 900 youths were rushing to move out from the main entrance as
soon as the gas was launched.
</P>
<P>
The modern 1,100-people capacity disco, named Discotheque
Luanda, is mostly frequented by the Angolans and Cape Verdeans
living in the Portuguese capital Lisbon.
</P>
<P>
Local analysts noticed that the incident followed the heated
argument last week on the issue of the entry visa, during which 27
Portuguese nationals and 12 Angolans had been barred from enter
Angola and Portugal.
</P>
<P>
According to the Angolan international airport, those
Portuguese visitors wanted to enter Angola for working but without
working permits. In a retaliatory action, the Portuguese airport
said that 12 Angolans lacked some documents for entering Portugal
and repatriated them to Angola. 
</P>
</TEXT>
