<HEADLINE> S. Africa Reports 4.2 Million HIV-Infected Cases </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, April 18 (Xinhua) -- About 4.2 million people in
South Africa had been infected with the Human Immunodeficiency
Virus (HIV) by the end of last year, said Health Minister Manto
Tshabalala-Msimang on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The national HIV prevalence rate for 1999 was 22.4 percent,
compared to 22.8 percent for 1998, the health minister said at a
news conference in Pretoria.
</P>
<P>
She said although HIV prevalence had increased in five
provinces, there was not a generalized increase in all geographic
areas.
</P>
<P>
"The 1999 findings suggest that South Africa may be seeing a
shift in the epidemiological profile of HIV, in which a small
degree of stabilization may be occurring," she said.
</P>
<P>
That does not necessarily mean that there were fewer cases of
HIV infection or there was a change in HIV incidence, although
that could be a contributing factor, Tshabalala-Msimang said.
</P>
<P>
The figures might have been influenced by factors like higher
mortality rates among HIV-infected people and fewer pregnancies
among HIV-infected women, she said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
