<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Foils U.S. Anti-China Attempt at U.N. Commission </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, April 18 (Xinhua) -- China foiled the United States'
anti-China attempt once again Tuesday as a "no-action motion" was
adopted at the 56th session of the United Nations Commission on
Human Rights.
</P>
<P>
The 53-member U.N. commission adopted the Chinese motion 22-18,
with 12 abstentions and 1 absent.
</P>
<P>
Qiao Zonghuai, Geneva-based ambassador from China, said that it
was China's ninth victory over the United States-led anti-China
attempt since 1990.
</P>
<P>
Despite the tremendous progress China has made in its human
rights conditions, the United States orchestrated another round of
anti-China campaign in 1999. The Americans failed to get anyone to
speak for it and had to come to the fore and act on its own.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. attempt was made mainly out of the needs of its
domestic politics. With presidential elections drawing nearer this
year, the United States tried once again to confront China at the
annual U.N. human rights commission meeting.
</P>
<P>
The Americans went so far as to resort to evil cults as its
weapons this year, accusing China of disrupting religious freedom.
The hard fact is that the first to expose the evils of Falun Gong
were exactly those from the Chinese religious circles themselves.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese government acted on Falun Gong in accordance with
the law of the country precisely for the purpose to protect the
freedom of belief of the more than 100 million Chinese cherishing
various regions.
</P>
<P>
The latest available statistics showed that upwards of 2,300
people fell prey to Falun Gong that either caused death, injury
and disability on its practitioners. The American attempt to heap
attacks upon China via an evil cult naturally would not round
backup from the countries and people who know where to draw the
line between good and evil.
</P>
<P>
"The draft resolution is nothing but an anti-China political
farce directed and played all by the United States alone, and a
mockery toward the (U.N.) human rights commission and its members,
" said Qiao, who also heads the Chinese delegation to the annual
six-week meeting of the commission.
</P>
<P>
China's motion of "no-action" was fully justified by the
existing statute, Qiao added. "The rules of procedure applied in
the Human Rights Commission were established by the Economic and
Social Council of the United Nations through legal procedures and
have been in effective use for many years."
</P>
<P>
No-action motions have been applied at numerous occasions and
have never been called into question, stressed the Chinese
ambassador.
</P>
<P>
"History has proven, and will continue to prove, that hegemony,
power politics and any attempt to control other people's destiny
can only lead to self-destruction," Qiao said.
</P>
<P>
"The brave strides of the 1.3 billion Chinese people can be
stopped by no one," he stressed", added Qiao. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
