<HEADLINE> Fishing Banned In Central China Lake </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHANGSHA, April 18 (Xinhua) -- A three-month fishing ban went
into effect today at Dongting Lake, one of the country's largest
freshwater lakes, in central China's Hunan Province..
</P>
<P>
All trawlers and fishing boats will be banned in a 60,000-
hectare area of the lake through June, according to a local
fishery official.
</P>
<P>
The province has decided to strictly supervise the fishing area
and prohibit all fishing activities during this period, he said.
</P>
<P>
During the ban, some 200,000 fishermen will be given training
and help in maintaining their vessels, the official said, adding
that the ban's purpose is to protect marine resources from over-
fishing which in the past ten years has significantly depleted
marine resources and caused a decline in the output of aquatic
products.
</P>
<P>
Dongting Lake has been fished for about 6,000 years, and there
are now 117 kinds of fish living in the lake. Last year, the lake
reported a fishery production value of 4.5 billion yuan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
