<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hong Kong Stocks Up After Wall St.'s Rebound </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The rebound followed the overnight recovery of the Wall Street,
which saw the Dow Jones Industrials rise 2.69 percent to close at
10,582.51 points and the Nasdaq post its biggest point gain, up
217.87 points or 6.56 percent to 3,539.16 points.
</P>
<P>
Analysts say that the recent turbulence on the market is an
appropriate correction with the global economic recovery as a
background.
</P>
<P>
The turnover on the Hong Kong market Tuesday totaled 12.586
billion HKD (1.6 billion USD), as against Monday's 15.102 billion
HKD (1.9 billion USD).
</P>
<P>
All of the four sub-indices of the benchmark Hang Seng Index
posted gains with Finance, Utilities, Properties and Commerce &AMP;
Industry going up 1.32 percent, 0.69 percent, 2.12 percent and 5.
36 percent respectively.
</P>
<P>
Hang Seng China Enterprises Index rose 10.64 percent, or 36
points, to 374.44 while the Hang Seng China-Affiliated Corp Index
gained 3.38 percent, or 40.84 points, to close at 1,250.81 points.
</P>
<P>
The HSI opened 395.78 points, or 2.68 percent, higher at 15,158.
15 points in the morning and closed the morning session at 15,310.
71 points, up 548.34 points, or 3.71 percent.
</P>
<P>
The Growth Enterprise market, Hong Kong's equivalent of the U.S.
Nasdaq market, soared 32.83 points, or 5.39 percent, to close at
641.86. 
</P>
</TEXT>
