<HEADLINE> Thai-Myanmar Border to be Narcotically Free by 2004 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Chetta was quoted by Thailand News Agency (TNA) as saying that
Thai and Myanmar authorities have agreed to eradicate drug
problems along the two country's 2,400-kilometer border by the
year 2004.
</P>
<P>
The general, who reportedly has good personal relations with
Myanmar leaders, said he helped the Thai government coordinating
with the Myanmar government to carry out crop-for-drug plantation
project.
</P>
<P>
The project, initiated by Thai king Bhumibol Adulyadej, will
help farmers along the border to plant economic crops instead of
drug-related plants, he said.
</P>
<P>
Drug problems along the Thai-Myanmar border will be gradually
addressed through concrete cooperation among all parties concerned,
the general said.
</P>
<P>
Drug-related plantation has jeopardized the social stability of
the two neighboring countries, TNA said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
