<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, April 18 (Xinhua) -- Germany has decided to
cancel the total debt valued at 62.7 million U.S. dollars owed by
Tanzania, the African newspaper reported on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The Tanzanian Minister for Finance Daniel Yona was quoted as
saying on Monday that Germany's decision is in line with the Paris
Club decision last week to cancel Tanzania's 1.88 billion U.S.
dollars debt.
</P>
<P>
The minister commended the German government for its decision
and requested other countries to follow the example.
</P>
<P>
He said the Tanzanian government will make efforts to convince
non-Paris Club countries to cancel their debts, which stood at 864
million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Yona, who had just arrived from Paris where he attended a Paris
Club meeting, explained that the debts canceled by the
International Monetary Fund (IMF), World Bank and the Paris Club
were for loans acquired before 1986 which are now mature for
payment.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this month, the World Bank and the IMF announced to
grant a two billion U.S. dollars debt relief for Tanzania, halving
the African country' s debt servicing bill for 2001-03 and
reducing it by a third in coming years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
