<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fresh Fighting Kills 16 Rebels in Sri Lanka </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, April 18 (Xinhua) -- At least 16 Tamil Tiger rebels
had been killed in fresh clashes in their separatist war against
Sri Lanka's government troops as the latest round of fighting
entered its fourth week in the country's north, the Ministry of
Defense said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The ministry said in a statement that troops on Monday killed
12 rebels of Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam (LTTE) in various
clashes in the northern Jaffna peninsula.
</P>
<P>
The peninsula has been the scene of some fierce fighting in the
past three weeks since the LTTE, fighting for a separate homeland
for minority Tamils in Sri Lanka's north and east since 1983,
launched a fresh push to capture their former stronghold of Jaffna.
</P>
<P>
The statement said troops also engaged a rebel bunker with
small arms and rocket propelled grenades at Janakapura in the
northern Welioya region, killing four rebels.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the international relief agency Medecins sans
Frontiers (MSF) has urged the Sri Lankan government to allow the
immediate re-supply of urgently needed drugs to the war-torn north
where stocks were running out.
</P>
<P>
MSF, or Doctors Without Borders, said in a statement issued on
Monday that in the past three months drug supplies had run low in
the northern Mullaithivu and Kilinochchi districts and attempts by
humanitarian agencies to renew supplies had been thwarted by
security forces.
</P>
<P>
"We are facing a situation where clinics and hospitals have
closed or are no longer accepting patients because they cannot
provide treatment for these civilians, many of whom are women and
children," Isabel Simpson, head of the Sri Lankan mission of MSF (
Netherlands) said in the statement.
</P>
<P>
A large part of Wanni region, where the Mullaithivu and
Kilinochchi districts are situated, is under LTTE control. Medical
supplies cannot be sent there without defense ministry permission.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
