<DOCNO> XIE20000418.0218 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Complete BSP System This Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, April 18 (Xinhua) -- China's civil aviation sector is
to complete the introduction of the Billing and Settlement Plan (
BSP), a widely-used system initiated by the International Air
Transport Association (IATA), in October.
</P>
<P>
Industry insiders said this is one of China's major endeavors
to standardize civil aviation administration.
</P>
<P>
They said that although China's civil aviation sector has
become profitable, there are still loopholes in management in this
area.
</P>
<P>
The BSP system is to simplify selling, reporting, and remitting
procedures for travel agency sales and the settlement of accounts
between carriers and their appointed sales agents.
</P>
<P>
Under the system, sales agents can issue standard tickets for
all the airlines joining in the plan, and all accounting and
settling are done within the system.
</P>
<P>
China decided to adopted the system in 1995 and has since made
significant progress in the effort.
</P>
<P>
IATA has had 150 BSPs around the world since the system was
initiated in 1971.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
