<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippine Lawmen on Alert vs. Extremists' Threats </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
In a press release issued here, National Security Adviser
Aguirre said there is continuing coordination among intelligence
agencies to verify the reported threat from the Abu Sayyaf group.
</P>
<P>
"We have what you call intelligence exchange and continuing
coordination and liaisoning among friendly forces. We are doing
this as part of a routine job," Aguirre said.
</P>
<P>
Chief Director Panfilo Lacson of the Philippine National Police
said in a separate radio speech that the police will beef up their
patrols and will continue to team up with the Philippine marines
to keep peace and order in Metro Manila.
</P>
<P>
According to reports, the Abu Sayyaf threatened Monday to kill
American nationals in the Philippines unless the government worked
for the release of three suspected international terrorists jailed
in he United States.
</P>
<P>
The Abu Sayyaf is now holding 29 civilian hostages, including
teachers and students in the southern Philippine province of
Basilan.
</P>
<P>
Aguirre also reiterated the government's position that it would
exhaust all peaceful means in seeking the safe release of the
hostages. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
