<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fatal Australian Encephalitis Cases Reported </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, April 17 (Xinhua) -- Eight cases of the potentially
fatal mosquito-borne disease Australian encephalitis have been
reported in the last three weeks from the Northern Territory and
Western Australia.
</P>
<P>
A baby is in a critical condition and a 45-year-old Victorian
man in a serious but stable condition, The Communicable Diseases
Network Australia New Zealand said Monday.
</P>
<P>
Above-average wet season rains and flooding across the
mentioned areas has facilitated the breeding of huge numbers of
the mosquito which transmits the disease.
</P>
<P>
Symptoms of Australian encephalitis include severe headache,
neck stiffness, high fevers, seizures in young children and
potentially delirium, coma and death.
</P>
<P>
AAP quoted a doctor as saying that "There is no cure and no
vaccine."
</P>
<P>
"The only sure way of preventing this disease is to avoid
mosquito bites altogether," the doctor said.
</P>
<P>
Encephalitis Protect Factbox were released by the Australian
mass media to tell residents how to avoid being stung by
mosquitoes. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
