<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading Israeli Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, April 18 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news
items in leading Israeli newspapers Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The Jerusalem Post:
</P>
<P>
-- Israel formally notified the United Nations Monday that it
would complete its withdrawal from Lebanon by July, and that it
expects the U.N. to fulfill its task in restoring international
peace and security.
</P>
<P>
The three-paragraph letter from Foreign Minister David Levy to
U.N. Secretary General Kofi Annan said the withdrawal would be
carried out in accordance with Security Council Resolutions 425 and
426.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli government "will do its utmost to assist the United
Nations and cooperate in performing its other tasks as encompassed
in the resolutions, including the restoration of international
peace and security," Levy's letter said.
</P>
<P>
Ha'aretz:
</P>
<P>
-- Israel's ministerial committee for the economy decided Monday
to build a facility capable of desalination 50 million cubic meters
of saltwater annually, with an option of doubling the figure in the
future.
</P>
<P>
The decision was reached after a discussion on how to deal with
the ongoing water crisis, concluding the committee's long argument
over bringing desalination to Israel. The cost of the facility is
estimated at 150 million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
The committee also decided to open negotiations with the Turkish
government to receive quotes for a 5-year contract to purchase an
annual quantity of some 45 million cubic meters of fresh water.
</P>
<P>
Ma'ariv:
</P>
<P>
-- At the initiative of Prime Minister and Defense Minister Ehud
Barak, the security cabinet is expected Tuesday to discuss and
approve a bill that would empower the defense minister to authorize
holding "enemy fighters in detention for the purpose of "redeeming
prisoners of war."
</P>
<P>
The panel is expected to pass the measure and then refer it to
the Knesset (Parliament), which may convene in special session as
early as Tuesday to put it to a preliminary vote, senior government
sources said.
</P>
<P>
The measure is being introduced after the Supreme Court Monday
rejected a desperate measure by families of those missing in action
to reverse a court ruling last week to free 13 Lebanese detainees
in Israeli prison.
</P>
<P>
Yediot Aharonot:
</P>
<P>
-- Big-name stocks rallied back Monday surging into the close
amid hopes that Wall Street had hit bottom in last week's punishing
selloff. Most other stocks fell again, however, as bargain hunters
remained leery of smaller companies.
</P>
<P>
In Tel Aviv trading Monday, prices were mixed in tense
anticipation of how the trading would fare on Wall Street.
</P>
<P>
At the end of the day, the benchmark Maof index gained a
moderate 1.5 percent, the Tel Aviv 100 index was up 1.3 percent,
and the Teltech went up by 1.8 percent after Sunday's 17 percent
free fall. 
</P>
</TEXT>
