<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zambia to Receive 50 Million U.S. Dollars From EU </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, April 18 (Xinhua) -- Zambia will this year receive more
than 53 million euro (about 50 million U.S. dollars) from the
European Union (EU) under phase-five of the Structural Adjustment
Facility (SAF), the Times of Zambia newspaper reported on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The EU will also release another six million euro (about 5.7
million U.S. dollars) to be used for handling of external tariff
rates once the Common Market for Eastern and Southern Africa
introduces the Free Trade Area on October 31, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Ambjorn Berglund, counsellor at the EU head-of-delegation
office in Lusaka, was quoted as saying in an interview on Monday
that discussions between the Zambian government and the EU are
currently underway and the proposals, once concluded, would be
sent to Brussels for approval.
</P>
<P>
"We have completed funding for phase-four and a feasibility
study is being done for phase-five," he said.
</P>
<P>
He said part of the previous SAF assistance was for the Public
Service Reform Program, particularly payment of retrenchees'
benefits.
</P>
<P>
The program has come at a time when Zambia is discussing new
conditionalities on poverty reduction with the International
Monetary Fund. 
</P>
</TEXT>
