<DOCNO> XIE20000418.0266 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bangladesh Yet to Benefit From Transit Accord With Nepal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, April 18 (Xinhua) -- Lack of concrete measures to
improve rail and road infrastructure is depriving Bangladesh of a
huge amount of foreign exchange earning from transit facilities
for Nepalese commodities, the Daily Star reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The report said Bangladesh could also develop its trucking
industry and create employment opportunity for a large number of
people in the service sector just by providing access to Mongla
Port, 200 km south of Dhaka, for a major portion of the over one
million tons of goods the land-locked Himalayan Kingdom exports
and imports every year.
</P>
<P>
Although Dhaka and Kathmandu had signed a transit agreement
more than two and a half years ago on September 1, 1997, the route
is still to be operational in the true sense through removal of a
number of impediments and the immediate signing of a comprehensive
motor vehicle agreement between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
The opportunity of handling almost the entire bulk of the
Nepalese cargo is now lost to Bangladesh as the cargo is routed
through India's Calcutta Port.
</P>
<P>
According to the report, Nepalese businessmen are very much
interested in using Mongla Port for transshipment of their goods,
but they are unable to use the port properly due to poor road
communication between the transit point and the port.
</P>
<P>
Experts in the country believed that in the long run, nearly
100 million U.S. dollars would have to be invested for improvement
of road communication between the country's northern districts and
Mongla Port to make Bangladesh-Nepal transit route operational.
</P>
<P>
Bangladesh could expect to get a quick return from the
investment as Nepal would be able to transship over one million
tons of cargo through Mongla Port instead of Calcutta.
</P>
<P>
The experts also noted that the Nepalese economy and the
businessmen would also immensely benefit from shipment through
Mongla Port as transportation through Bangladesh would be cheaper
and faster. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
