<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesian Military Chief Meets U.N. Commander </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, April 18 (Xinhua) -- The Indonesia Military (TNI) and
the United Nations Peacekeeping Force (UNPKF) in East Timor are
both committed to jointly solving any problem arising on the
border between East Timor and Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
"Through cooperation based on mutual understanding between the
two sides, we hope all problems in the field can be properly
solved," TNI Commander Admiral Widodo A.S. said after a meeting
with UNPKF Commander Maj. Gen. de Los Santos at Laktutus village
near the East Timor-East Nusa Tenggara province border on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Widodo said he had met Santos several times before but Monday's
meeting at the foot of a hill was of special significance "as we
are both strongly committed to forge relations of mutual
cooperation to settle any border problem that may arise."
</P>
<P>
On April 11, the TNI and the UNPKF have signed a new agreement
on coordination of the maintenance of security in the border
regions between East Nusa Tenggara and East Timor.
</P>
<P>
Laktutus in Rasifeto Barat sub-district, about 45 kilometers
south of Atambua, was one of two villages where Widodo inspected
TNI border posts. The other village he visited was Builal in
Lamaknen sub-district.
</P>
<P>
Elaborating on his tour of the border regions, Widodo said he
wanted to personally observe conditions in the field.
</P>
<P>
"I am visiting the border with the three service chiefs (army,
navy and air force) and several other military officials to see
conditions in the field," he was quoted by the Antara News Agency
Tuesday as saying.
</P>
<P>
Widodo said the stationing of the soldiers at the border was an
important part of the government's effort to maintain a real
capability to act swiftly to settle border problems.
</P>
<P>
On the question of East Timor refugees who were still staying
in East Nusa Tenggara, Widodo said the Indonesian government fully
supported their repatriation.
</P>
<P>
He said 155,000 out of an initial 280,000 refugees had already
been repatriated.
</P>
<P>
"We always support those who wish to return to East Timor and
try to seek resettlement for those who wish to stay," he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000418.0271 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> hke041817 --Philippines Urged to Improve Technology, Productivity </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, April 18 (Xinhua) -- The Philippines needs to upgrade
its capacity to improve technology and productivity if it wants to
be at par with its neighboring countries in terms of industrial
development, an academic report said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The paper, entitled "Designing S &AMP; T Policy for the new
Millennium," is an outcome of the joint effort of the Institute of
Developing Economies and the University of the Philippines School
of Economics.
</P>
<P>
"The Philippines lags behind its Asian neighbors in
productivity and technological development. This does not deny
that some domestic firms, particularly the conglomerates, operate
at the frontiers which allow them to compete in the global market,
but there are only a few of them," the paper noted.
</P>
<P>
"Overall, the constrained capacity of the economy to absorb and
adopt innovations has only caused its gap with technological
leaders to widen over the years," the paper added.
</P>
<P>
According to the paper, the problem has long been diagnosed and
very few Filipinos are skilled in science and technology labor.
</P>
<P>
The recent count of research and development personnel in the
country, the paper said, is placed at 155 scientists and engineers
per million population, far below the standard of 380 scientist
and engineers per million population, which was set by the United
Nations Educational, Scientific and Cultural Organization (UNESCO).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000418.0272 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ADB Lends 5 Billion Dollars in 1999 (Embargoed Till 16:00 GMT, Tuesday, April 18) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, April 18 (Xinhua) -- The Asian Development Bank (ADB)
said Tuesday that it approved 66 loans totaling about 5 billion U.
S. dollars in 1999 for 52 projects, of which about 40 percent was
focused on poverty reduction.
</P>
<P>
Last November, the ADB approved a poverty reduction strategy
that elevates poverty reduction as the overarching goal of its
operations, the Manila-based bank said in its 1999 Annual Report
released here.
</P>
<P>
In 1999, ADB continued to extend financial assistance to
countries hit by the financial crisis, the bank said.
</P>
<P>
It provided nearly 100 million dollars in grants from its newly
created Asian Currency Crisis Support Facility in the form of
technical assistance and interest payment assistance to the
countries worst hit by the crisis.
</P>
<P>
Of the total lending in 1999, concessional loans from the Asian
Development Fund (ADF) to countries with low per capita gross
national product and limited debt repayment capacity rose 8
percent to over 1 billion dollars, the bank said.
</P>
<P>
The bank said China received the largest share of lending (
eight loans totaling 1.2 billion dollars for six projects) and
technical assistance (28 grants for nearly 20 million dollars) in
1999.
</P>
<P>
Other top borrowers in 1999 include Indonesia (1 billion
dollars), India (625 million dollars), Pakistan (402 million
dollars), Thailand (363 million dollars), Bangladesh (332 million
dollars), Vietnam (195 million dollars) and Sri Lanka (183 million
dollars), it sad.
</P>
<P>
"Loans from ADF made up 22 percent of total lending while the
rest came from ADB's ordinary capital resources (OCR)," it said.
</P>
<P>
Since ADB started operation in 1966, its cumulative lending as
of 1999 has amounted to 82 billion dollars in public and private
sector loans involving 1,550 projects in 38 developing members.
Nearly 2 billion dollars have been provided in technical
assistance grants and 600 million has gone to equity investments
and underwritings. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000418.0273 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Asia's Water Situation A "Human Tragedy": ADB  (Embargoed Till 16:00 GMT Tuesday, April 18) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, April 18 (Xinhua) -- The Asian Development Bank (ADB)
Tuesday described as "a major human Tragedy" Asia's water
situation and urged Asian governments to take the improvement of
the situation as one of their highest priorities.
</P>
<P>
In its 1999 Annual Report released here, the Manila-based bank
said that some 830 million people in developing Asia and the
Pacific do not have safe drinking water, and more than 2 billion
people lack sanitation facilities.
</P>
<P>
"In ADB's DMCs (developing member countries), an estimated 737
million people in rural areas and 93 million in urban areas still
have no access to safe drinking water," it said in the report's
theme chapter "Water in the 21st Century."
</P>
<P>
The bank said that access to sanitation is denied to 1.74
billion people in rural areas and 298 million in urban areas.
</P>
<P>
"This is a major human tragedy; provision of such services to
all people should be one of the highest priorities of all
governments," the bank said.
</P>
<P>
The bank said that while water pollution is the region's most
serious environmental problem, water scarcity will soon affect
food security in some parts of the region, which could lead to a
heightening tension between countries sharing the water resources
of international rivers.
</P>
<P>
Many Asian cities, where 56 percent of the population will live
by 2025, are ill equipped to provide their growing population the
safe water and sanitation they need, and up to one in four in the
region lacks formal sanitation, the bank said.
</P>
<P>
It said the poor are most prone to disease caused by unsafe
drinking water and inadequate sanitation.
</P>
<P>
"Almost 250 million cases of water-borne disease -- and 10
million deaths -- are reported worldwide each year," the bank said.
</P>
<P>
The bank said its water projects promote integrated water
resource management and it also encourage private sector water
initiatives through direct financial support.
</P>
<P>
At the policy level, the ADB said, it helps governments develop
master plans for the management of critical resources. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
