<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Drought Plagues South Korea </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, April 18 (Xinhua) -- A drought has hit South Korea over
the past two months, the Korea Meteorological Administration (KMA)
said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The KMA forecast that the drought will continue for some time
and affect negatively the growth of onions, garlic and other
spring crops.
</P>
<P>
Rains will set in on Wednesday and Friday across the nation but
they are not enough to quell the drought, said the administration.
</P>
<P>
Dry weather was registered for Seoul and Kyonggi and Kangwon
provinces for the past 59 days, the longest spell of drought
recorded in the past 10 years.
</P>
<P>
Seoul has received just 95 millimeters of rain since March 1,
the least since 1907 when the country began to keep record on
precipitation.
</P>
<P>
The country's four major dams -- Hapchon, Imha, Chungju and
Juam -- had a total of 5.9 billion tons of water as of Monday,
down 1 billion tons from a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
A strong high atmospheric pressure continues to reside in the
Korean Peninsula, preventing a low atmospheric pressure from
approaching.
</P>
<P>
Some rains that fell in the southern part of the country
recently did not help stop the spring drought, said the
administration. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
