<HEADLINE> Former Tajik President Joins Parliament </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ALMA ATA, April 17 (Xinhua) -- Former Tajik President Kakhal
Makhkamov was elected into the central Asian state's legislative
body at a parliament session held on Monday, said reports reaching
here from the Tajik capital Dushanbe.
</P>
<P>
Makhkamov, who served as the first president of the former
Soviet republic from November 1990 to August 1991, became the 34th
member of the upper house.
</P>
<P>
The country's constitution, however, stipulates that the upper
house comprises 33 members, with 25 of them elected from regions
and the rest 8 appointed by the President.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Mahmadsayd Ubaydullayev was elected the chairman of
the upper house. The former mayor of Dushanbe comes from the
ruling Tajikistan's People's Democratic Party.
</P>
<P>
Tajik President Emomali Rakhmonov attended the Monday session.
</P>
</TEXT>
