<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Colombia's Main Petroleum Pipeline Paralyzed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BOGOTA, April 17 (Xinhua) -- Colombia's main oil pipeline
leading from Cano Limon to the Caribbean port of Covenas has been
paralyzed since Thursday by a bomb explosion, said Colombian
Petroleum Company (COPETROL) Monday.
</P>
<P>
The company said the blast occurred at a rich oil field in
Arauca, but it didn't know when the incident had happened.
</P>
<P>
At least three other explosions were registered over the
weekend in the country and damage was detected in three other
sections, the company added.
</P>
<P>
The authorities attributed the sabotages to the National
Liberation Army guerrilla force that opposes the exploitation of
mineral resources by multinationals.
</P>
<P>
Colombia has reported 21 explosions on the pipeline so far this
year.
</P>
<P>
The 780-kilometer pipeline carries crude from oil fields near
Venezuela to the Caribbean port of Covenas for export. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
