<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Relations With China Central Element in Sweden's Foreign Policy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
STOCKHOLM, April 17 (Xinhua) -- Sweden attaches importance to
developing relations with China and hails the progress China has
made during the past few decades, the Swedish Foreign Ministry
said.
</P>
<P>
Sweden has devoted much attention to contacts and cooperation
with China, the world's most populous country, since they
established diplomatic ties on May 9, 1950 and particularly during
the past 20 years when China's role in international politics and
economy has become "more and more evident," the ministry said in
an information sheet.
</P>
<P>
The information sheet was released recently to commemorate the
50th anniversary of the establishment of diplomatic ties between
the two countries.
</P>
<P>
China occupies "an important place" in the Swedish government's
Asian strategy which the parliament adopted last year, and
developing relations with China has become "a central element" in
its foreign policy, according to the information sheet.
</P>
<P>
It's beneficial to both countries to enhance exchanges in as
many fields as possible, it said.
</P>
<P>
In terms of trade, the ministry said China has become Sweden's
second largest trading partner in Asia, and that the country's
export to and import from China has increased rapidly during the
1990s.
</P>
<P>
It welcomes China's entry into the World Trade Organization,
believing that it can help Swedish enterprises to expand their
operations in China.
</P>
<P>
The two countries will organize a series of activities to
celebrate the anniversary, including a visit to China of a Swedish
delegation in May this year to be led by Deputy Prime Minister
Lena Hjelm-wallen, the information sheet said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
