<DOCNO> XIE20000418.0303 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: IMF, World Bank Pledge to Promote Global Progress </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 17 (Xinhua) -- The Spring meetings of the
International Monetary Fund (IMF) and the World Bank concluded
Monday with renewed pledges to maintain sustainable world economic
growth for the global progress.
</P>
<P>
Central Bank officials and financial ministers from over 180
IMF-World Bank members participated in the two-day meetings, which
were held against the background of strong recovery of the world
economy following the financial crisis in Asian countries.
</P>
<P>
The Development Committee, the policy-setting group of the
World Bank, stressed in the communique issued Monday the
importance of international trade and poverty reduction for global
progress, equity and stability.
</P>
<P>
The committee urged the world's rich nations to do more to open
their markets to the world's poorest countries. And it also
pledged to work with the IMF to overhaul internal operations to
make both institutions more effective in fighting future global
financial crises.
</P>
<P>
On the issue of poverty reduction strategies, the committee
called on the IMF and the World Bank to allocate adequate
resources to support the Poverty Reduction Strategy Paper (PRSP)
process.
</P>
<P>
The committee also encouraged the governments of the Heavily
Indebted Poor Countries (HIPC) to continue to work closely with
the World Bank and the IMF as well as other partners in pursuing
sound policies and delivering effective reform programs so that
the delivery of HIPC debt relief and the related poverty reduction
strategies can move forward as swiftly as possible.
</P>
<P>
Another communique issued Sunday by the International Monetary
and Financial Committee, the policy-making body of the IMF, said
the agency will continue to work toward making it more effective,
transparent and accountable so it can better prevent financial
turbulence.
</P>
<P>
The committee stressed it will seek greater debt relief for the
poorest countries and reiterated the critical importance of open
and competitive markets as a key component of efforts to sustain
growth and stability in the global economy and to reduce poverty.
</P>
<P>
Prior to the IMF-World Bank meetings, ministers of the
Intergovernmental Group of Twenty-Four (G-24) on International
Monetary Affairs also held the 63rd meeting. The participants
complained the current trade policy stance of industrial nations
constitutes a major barrier to their growth prospects.
</P>
<P>
The ministers emphasized in a communique the need for a well-
sequenced and balanced approach toward the further integration of
developing countries, particularly the poorest, into the global
trading system.
</P>
<P>
The G-24 consists of an important cross section of countries in
Asia, Africa and Latin America. Since its establishment in 1972,
the organization becomes the primary institutional mechanism for
the coordination of developing country positions on monetary
affairs.
</P>
<P>
The IMF-World Bank meetings were overshadowed by thousands of
anti-globalization protesters who failed in efforts to shut down
the sessions but succeeded in putting a spotlight on complaints
that both institutions have failed in their job of alleviating
global poverty.
</P>
<P>
The demonstrators had complained during a week of escalating
protests that World Bank policies made poor countries even poorer
and that the bank and the IMF were not doing enough to aid debtor
states.
</P>
<P>
World Bank and IMF officials, for their part, declared a
victory because they were able to avoid the violent confrontations
that occurred last year in Seattle where police used tear gas and
rubber bullets to control the streets and a small number of
demonstrators looted and vandalized downtown buildings. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
