<HEADLINE> Economic News Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 18 (Xinhua) -- Following are today's economic
news in brief:
</P>
<P>
Tibet Conducts Technical Transformation
</P>
<P>
The government of Tibet Autonomous Region will allocate 430
million yuan to upgrade technology and equipment at 84 key state-
owned industrial enterprises this year.
</P>
<P>
 Poorest Region Gets Rich by Growing Potato
</P>
<P>
Potato production has become a pillar industry in Dingxi
Prefecture, one of the poorest areas in northwest China's Gansu
province. The region sown potato on 166,600 ha of land last year.
On average, each farmer earned 700 yuan from potato production
last year.
</P>
<P>
The prefecture sells more than 1 million tons of potato to
other parts of the country each year. Meanwhile, the 200-odd
starch processing factories consumed several million tons potato
annually. The prefecture will import equipment for making potato
chips, according to a contract signed with an overseas firm
recently.
</P>
<P>
 Ningxia Issues New Investment Regulations
</P>
<P>
Northwest China's Ningxia Hui Autonomous Region recently issued
a series of policies on foreign investment.
</P>
<P>
Newly-built exclusive foreign-funded enterprises in Ningxia
will be returned the income tax they paid to the state in the
first five years of operation.
</P>
<P>
Foreign companies are encouraged to invest in the fields of
agriculture, forestry, fishery, infrastructure and service trade.
</P>
<P>
 State Development Zones Built in Western China
</P>
<P>
The Kunming Economic and Technological Development Zone was
recently upgraded to a state-listed development zone as a measure
to improve investment environment there.
</P>
<P>
The development zone, in southwest China's Yunnan Province, has
signed four contracts involving a total investment of 300 million
yuan since its status was upgraded.
</P>
<P>
To date, the State Council has upgraded seven regional
development zones in the western part of China to the state-level.
</P>
</TEXT>
