<BODY>
<HEADLINE> More Birds Inhabit in N. China Nature Reserve </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HOHHOT, April 18 (Xinhua) -- Efforts made by China's natural
conservation staff are turning Dalai Lake near China's north
border into a better home for birds.
</P>
<P>
A latest survey conducted by a group of scientists showed that
nearly 100 species of birds are now inhabiting around the lake
which has been set as one of China's some 1,000 nature reserves.
</P>
<P>
Among the 100 bird species found around the lake, 22 are new
ones that had not been recorded before in the area, the survey
indicated.
</P>
<P>
Scientists believe that the nature reserve, 7,400 sq. km in
area, has come to be an important route and habitat for birds
migrating between northeast Asia to Australia.
</P>
<P>
To better protect the wetland and grassland ecosystems there, a
joint research project attended by scientists from China, Russia
and Mongolia has already been launched, scientists say. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000418.0308 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Landslide in Tibet Causes No Casualties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LHASA, April 18 (Xinhua) -- No one was killed or injured in a
large-scale landslide in Powo County, southwest China's Tibet
Autonomous Region, according to reports reaching here today.
</P>
<P>
The landslide occurred around 08:00 pm last Saturday. Nearly
500 million cubic meters of mud and stone rolled down the mountain
slope and blocked Yigong River, pushing the water level at the
river's upper reaches above the warning line. More than 4,000
residents in two nearby townships were stranded.
</P>
<P>
Up to now, over 1,000 local residents have been moved to safer
areas. There has been no spread of epidemic disease in the region.
</P>
<P>
Governments at various levels in Tibet have allocated 1.6
million yuan in relief funds and shipped food, butter, tent to
other relief materials to help local residents tide over temporary
difficulties.
</P>
<P>
A rush repair team has been sent to the affected area to build
a simple road. Though they worked day and night, only a 1.5-km-
long road has been got through on account of loosen earth by now.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
