<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Foreign Mining Firms Delay Exploration Activities in Indonesia  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, April 18 (Xinhua) -- Due to the security uncertainty
or financial problems, at least 16 foreign mining companies have
delayed their activities in Indonesia, a senior government
official was quoted by the Jakarta Post Tuesday as saying.
</P>
<P>
The 16 companies, which obtained their contracts of work
between 1996 and 1998 to explore and produce mineral resources
other than coal, were mostly in the exploration stage.
</P>
<P>
Some companies, which are mostly from Canada and Australia,
temporarily stopped their exploration due to security reasons
while others quit mining operations due to financial difficulties
encountered by their parent companies.
</P>
<P>
"With Indonesia's current uncertain social and economic
situation, it's understandable if people hesitate to invest here,"
said Simon Sembiring, director of mining development at the
Ministry of Mines and Energy.
</P>
<P>
He said Indonesia's newly founded democracy had resulted in
outbursts of regional discontent over mining and timber operations,
which many said have so far only benefited the central government.
The dissatisfaction has often led to conflicts between the local
community and mining companies.
</P>
<P>
The delay in the 16 companies' projects would result in a sharp
decline in investment spending in the country's mining sector
because each company generally spends about 5 million to 10
million U.S. dollars a year on exploration activities.
</P>
<P>
"There is no particular loss for Indonesia," Simon said. But he
added that the delay directly affected local workers who were
forced to leave their jobs. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
