<HEADLINE> Majority of U.S. Investors Still Confident of Stock Market: Poll </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, April 17 (Xinhua) -- A majority of American
investors remain bullish about the stock market and the economy
generally, despite recent stock market declines, according to
results from a weekend poll released Monday.
</P>
<P>
Those who have sold or bought shares last year are even more
bullish than the general population, said the poll.
</P>
<P>
The results are from a survey of nearly 900 adults conducted by
the Angus Reid Group, one of North American's premier market
research and public opinion polling firms, over the weekend in the
wake of one of the biggest single day drops in U.S. stock market
history last Friday.
</P>
<P>
"So far," said the firm, on analyzing the results, "the recent
market upheaval has not eroded consumer confidence and most
Americans feel the economy remains strong."
</P>
<P>
Of the adults surveyed, 68 percent agree with the statement
that "the recent declines in the stock market are part of a normal
adjustment and the underlying American economy is as strong as
ever." Twenty-seven percent feel that "the recent declines point
to fundamental weaknesses in the American economy."
</P>
<P>
Over half of them say that they would advise their friends and
family to continue to invest in the stock market. 
</P>
</TEXT>
