<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Internet Users Going Wireless </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
At presently, one-third of the U.S. population uses cell phones
for business purposes. Of this group, only 11 percent are
currently using them for data applications, said the report on the
research conducted by Cap Gemini America, an information
technology consulting service leader. In the research, based on a
survey of 1,000 Internet users in the United States, wireless data
applications entail using a cell phone to send and receive e-mail
or business/personal information.
</P>
<P>
Forty-seven percent of the future users explained that the
primary reason for using wireless data applications is that
someone else (i.e., the employer) pays for it. This was by far the
most important reason, according to the research, and consequently,
market growth will initially be driven by corporate initiatives
rather than consumer demand.
</P>
<P>
According to an earlier study by U.S. market research firm
International Data Corporation (IDC), more than 40 million U.S.
households are online, but there are more than 75 million cellular/
wireless services subscribers and more than 40 million paging
subscribers. By the end of 2002, there will be more wireless
subscribers capable of Internet access than wired Internet users
in the United States. When this happens, IDC said, there will be a
fundamental shift in the thinking of the Web community and the
information technology industry as a whole. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000418.0328 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Guangzhou Steps Up Refuse Treatment (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, April 18 (Xinhua) -- With completion of the Datansha
Garbage Incineration Plant by 2001, this provincial capital of
Guangdong in south China will greatly expand its refuse treatment.
</P>
<P>
The plant built with a government funding of some 700 million
yuan will have an annual capacity of 126 million kilowatt hours of
electricity. It will consume 900 tons of garbage a day.
</P>
<P>
The city's households generate 4,300 tons of garbage a day or 1.
56 million tons a year. The figure will rise to 2.15 million tons
in ten years.
</P>
<P>
The municipal environmental protection department expected that
the fledgling commercial garbage treatment industry will be able
to consume 70 percent of the garbage then.
</P>
<P>
In addition to Datansha, the city government has also invested
in a number of high-tech garbage treatment plants. Guangzhou has
set up a household garbage classification center, where refuse is
sorted for separate treatment.
</P>
<P>
A landfill ground that costs 370 million yuan of investment was
launched early this year and will be completed by 2002. It is
designed to take in 2,500 tons of garbage a day, to be in
operation for 17 years.
</P>
<P>
Also under construction are the Sanxin Biological Fertilizer
Plant, which will use biochemical technology to decompose kitchen
refuse into organic fertilizer, and turn waste plastics into
gasoline and diesel oil. The plant is expected to consume 450,000
tons of garbage a year, turning out 50,000 tons of fertilizer and
10,000 tons of gasoline and diesel.
</P>
<P>
The municipal environmental protection department is
negotiating with several companies from Japan and the U.S. for
joint ventures to generate electricity by burning refuse.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
