<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Beijing's Foreigners-oriented Garments Market Loses Glamour </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 18 (Xinhua) -- The Yabaolu garments market,
which used to attract flocks of foreign business people and
tourists, has lost its glamour now.
</P>
<P>
The market, originally located along the four-hundred-meter
long Yabaolu Street, came into being in the year 1988. Over 4,000
Chinese traders sold clothing and toys with Chinese
characteristics, and tens of thousands of foreigners, among them
many Russians, would go there everyday for silk clothes, T-shirts
with Beijing Opera mask designs, and cheong-sams (Qipao) in the
over 2,000 boutiques.
</P>
<P>
Garment exports to Russia hit 800 million U.S. dollars in its
climax, accounting for a large proportion of the city's total
exports business.
</P>
<P>
A 30,000 sq m trade building was set up in 1998, wishing to
attract more foreigners. However, customers have decreased rapidly
due to the sluggish economy in Russia and the construction of
other shopping centers nearby.
</P>
<P>
Now one quarter of the trading hall is occupied by stalls
selling fresh vegetables, meat and fruits.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000418.0333 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shandong Plagued With Severe Drought </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JINAN, April 18 (Xinhua) -- East China's Shandong Province has
been afflicted with increasingly severe drought, due to the lack
of rainfall and recent serious sandstorms.
</P>
<P>
By April 15, about 928,700 ha. of farmland have become dry,
according to the local water conservancy department.
</P>
<P>
From March 1 to April 14, local rainfall was averaged at only
three millimeters, a 91 percent decline from the normal level and
a 84 percent decrease from the 1999 figure.
</P>
<P>
The volume of water stored up in local big and medium-sized
reservoirs and major lakes also drops to 3.866 billion cubic
meters, 900 million cubic meters less than the normal level, and
water reserved on land surface also decreases by 1.5 billion cubic
meters to four billion cubic meters.
</P>
<P>
However, the province is exerting great effort to save water,
in a bid to ensure a good agricultural harvest for the year.
</P>
</TEXT>
