<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Holland Adheres to One-China Policy, Backs China's WTO Membership  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
THE HAGUE, Netherlands, April 17 (Xinhua) -- The government of
the Netherlands promised to China Monday that it will continue to
uphold the One-China policy and actively support China's bid to
join the World Trade Organization.
</P>
<P>
In her meeting here with visiting Chinese Vice Premier Li
Lanqing, Vice Prime Minister Annemarie Jorritsma-Lebbink, who
doubles as the Minister for Economic Affairs, said the Dutch
government attaches great importance to developing ties with China.
</P>
<P>
She noted that in recent years, with the joint efforts of the
two governments, economic and trade relations between the two
countries developed rapidly, featuring many successful projects.
Meantime, cooperation between the two countries in the field of
science and technology was strengthened, she added.
</P>
<P>
The Dutch vice premier said that the current official visit to
the Netherlands by the Chinese Vice Premier will help push forward
the bilateral relations.
</P>
<P>
Li Lanqing, who arrived here Sunday on a three-day official
visit, agreed with his Holland counterpart, on appreciating what
he described as "fruitful" cooperation between China and the
Netherlands in the areas of economic and trade, science and
technology, culture, and educations.
</P>
<P>
He said that the Chinese government will continue to work
together with the Dutch government to further strengthen bilateral
cooperation in every possible field on the basis of mutual benefit,
because this, as he stressed, is in the long-term interests of the
two nations.
</P>
<P>
During their talks, the Chinese Premier also stressed that the
process of economic globalization should be pushed forward in a
healthy way.
</P>
<P>
In this regard, he said that efforts should be made to promote
multi-polarization of the world and to maintain the interests of
the developing countries.
</P>
<P>
It is the obligation of the developed nations to try to
alleviate the debt burden of the developing nations and truly open
their markets to the products from the developing countries, Li
stressed.
</P>
<P>
As diversified the world is, Li said the differences among
nations in their social systems, culture, history, and stages of
economic development should be respected.
</P>
<P>
Only by doing so can countries in the world co-exist peacefully
and achieve common development, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
