<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at GMT0045, April 18 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME -- Italian Premier Massimo D'Alema went to President Carlo
Azeglio Ciampi Monday evening to offer his resignation, after his
center-left's defeat in Sunday's regional elections, but was told
by the president to return to Parliament and seek a vote of
confidence.
</P>
<P>
The protocol used meant that Ciampi did not accept D'Alema's
resignation on the grounds that Parliament was the proper forum to
verify whether he was still in a position to govern, a spokesman
for the presidential Quirinale Palace explained. (BC-Italy-
President)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
NAIROBI -- Major General Paul Kagame was elected the fifth
Rwandan president Monday by 81 votes of 86 members of the cabinet
and parliament, Rwanda News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The 65 Members of Parliament and 21 Cabinet members cast a
secret ballot in a swift presidential election, with the other
candidate Charles Murigande getting five votes. (BC-Rwanda-
President)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
HARARE -- Zimbabwean President Robert Mugabe Monday met the
leaders of white commercial farmers to discuss the occupation of
about 1,000 farms by the black liberation war veterans.
</P>
<P>
President of the Commercial Farmers' Union Tim Henwood and
President of Zimbabwe Tobacco Association Richard Tate held a two-
hour meeting with Mugabe, which they described as fruitful and "
very good", the Zimbabwe News Agency reported. (BC-Zimbabwe-Farm-
Invasion)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BOGOTA -- Colombia's air force has destroyed two light aircraft
with Brazilian registration that entered the country with weapons
guerrilla were going to pay with cocaine, said military
authorities.
</P>
<P>
Commander of the Colombian Air Force (FAC) General Hector
Fabio Velasco said Monday that the Brazilian airplanes were
destroyed while they were carrying out illegal flights on
Colombian territory. (BC-Colombia-Brazil-Air Fight)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- U.S. President Bill Clinton decided Monday
against the sale of four Aegis destroyers to Taiwan but approved
sale of long-range radar designed to detect missile launches, AP
quoted a senior U.S. official as saying.
</P>
<P>
Clinton, who is in California on a tour of impoverished
communities, acted on the recommendation of top advisers who met
earlier in the day at the White House, said the official, who
spoke on condition of anonymity. (BC-US-Clinton-Taiwan) 
</P>
