<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenyans Win Boston Marathon Titles </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 17 (Xinhua) -- Kenyans dominated the Boston
Marathon by winning both the men's and the women's races in Boston
on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Elijah Lagat won the men's title with a time of 2 hours, 9
minutes and 47 seconds while Catherine Ndereba won the women's
race, upsetting defending three-time champion Fatuma Roba of
Ethiopia in a time of 2:26.11. Roba finished third.
</P>
<P>
Two-time winner Moses Tanui of Kenya broke from a three-man
pack about 400 meters from the finish but was caught by fellow
countryman Lagat, who sprinted ahead for the victory in his first
Boston race.
</P>
<P>
Ethiopia's Gezahenge Abera finished second in the same time as
Lagat, with Tanui third in 2:09:50. It was the closest three-man
finish in the 104-year history of the Boston race, officials said.
</P>
<P>
Lagat and Tanui earned a trip to this year's Olympic Games in
Sydney as Kenya used the race as its Olympic qualifier.
</P>
<P>
Irina Bogacheva of Kyrgyzstan finished second in the women's
race. 
</P>
</TEXT>
