<DOCNO> XIE20000418.0344 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Construction on China's First Solely Foreign-Funded Hydropower Station </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XINING, April 18 (Xinhua) -- Construction on China's first
solely foreign-funded hydropower station on the Yellow River will
begin soon, said an official from northwest China's Qinghai
Provincial Planning Commission.
</P>
<P>
The Zhiganglaka Hydropower Station on the upper reaches of the
Yellow River is solely financed by the U.S.-based Aes TB Power
Company Limited jointly funded by the Aes Orient Inc and the Hong
Kong-based Truf Busy Group Limited.
</P>
<P>
The station, to be constructed at the juncture of Jianzha and
Hualong counties in Qinghai, will be the first medium-sized
station solely funded by a foreign investor and also the largest
foreign-funded project of Qinghai Province.
</P>
<P>
The station will cost about 1.3 billion yuan and have an
installed generating capacity of 192,000 kilowatts. The whole
project will be completed in three and a half years.
</P>
<P>
The station, only seven kilometers away from the Lijiaxia
Hydropower Station, is expected to generate 762 million kw of
electricity a year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000418.0345 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fujian Clamps Down On Pirated VCD, DVD Producers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
FUJIAN, April 18 (Xinhua) -- Copyright protection authorities
in east China's Fujian province have dealt harshly with the
pirated VCD and DVD producers with over 70,000 discs confiscated
since the beginning of this year.
</P>
<P>
Fujian police have cracked down on two production lines that
manufacture pirated VCDs and DVDs since 1997.
</P>
<P>
Early this week, the province handed out rewards to those with
information concerning pirated activities and their offenders.
Those who report illegal VCD and DVD production lines will be
awarded for up to 300,000 yuan (36,150 U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
Those who report assembling such production lines will receive
30,000 to 100,000 yuan (3,620 to 12,500 U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
An official from the Fujian Provincial Press and Publication
Bureau said that rewards aim to encourage people to keep a close
eye on these illegal activities. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000418.0346 </DOCNO>
