<DOCNO> XIE20000418.0347 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Prefer Planned Consumption: Survey </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 18 (Xinhua) -- A recent survey by the China
Youth Daily shows that most young people are spending money
according to their family budget, but they are not saving as much.
</P>
<P>
The survey was conducted on more than 8,000 people from 31
provinces, autonomous regions and municipalities across the
country. Among them, 64.3 percent are men, and 83.6 percent are
below 31 years old. More than 95 percent of people have a high
school or higher education.
</P>
<P>
According to the survey, 72.7 percent of the surveyed said that
spending in accordance with their family budget is the most ideal
way of consumption.
</P>
<P>
Experts said there are two kinds of family budget. One is to
spend money according to the amount of money they earn, and the
other is trying to earn as much money as the family budget needs.
</P>
<P>
Only 5.5 percent thought that to spend all the money they earn
is an ideal way of consumption, but as many as 13.9 percent of
people surveyed are actually spending all their income.
</P>
<P>
About 10.9 percent said they will try bank loans or credits to
buy houses or invest in other projects.
</P>
<P>
Sixty-two percent said that their parents like to save as much
money as possible and 33.6 percent said they make plans and then
spend the money accordingly.
</P>
<P>
The survey also shows that very few people from the older
generation (about 1.4 percent) would agree to use bank loans or
credit to purchase consumer goods.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000418.0348 </DOCNO>
