<BODY>
<HEADLINE> O'Sullivan Crashes in Snooker Worlds First Round </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 17 (Xinhua) -- Ronnie O'Sullivan was knocked out
of the world snooker championships when he lost to qualifier David
Gray 10-9 in first round in Sheffield, England on Monday.
</P>
<P>
O'Sullivan followed defending champion Stephen Hendry who
crashed out on Saturday to another qualifier Stuart Bingham.
</P>
<P>
Another potential upset was avoided when England's Anthony
Hamilton ended the championship hopes of Hong Kong's Marco Fu with
a 10-4 first-round win.
</P>
<P>
Gray's victory was even more remarkable as he had to fight back
from 5-1 down after O'Sullivan registered century breaks in three
successive games.
</P>
<P>
In another match which started in the evening session, Welshman
Matthew Stevens established a commanding 7-2 lead over Malta's
Tony Drago.
</P>
<P>
Stevens, who has reached the quarter-finals for the last two
years, raced to a 5-0 lead before Drago got off the mark in the
sixth frame.
</P>
<P>
Drago won the last frame of the night to trail by five frames.
</P>
<P>
Ireland's Ken Doherty, who won the title three years ago, leads
Darren Morgan of Wales 6-3. 
</P>
</TEXT>
