<HEADLINE> Mubarak Discusses Bilateral Ties, Regional Issues with Romanian FM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, April 18 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak met
on Tuesday with Romanian Minister of State and Foreign Minister
Petre Roman and the two discussed the bilateral economic relations
and regional issues of common concern.
</P>
<P>
Roman told reporters after the meeting that Mubarak fully
supports the efforts to develop the ties of cooperation between
Romania and Egypt, especially in the economic and trade fields.
</P>
<P>
He termed the Romanian-Egyptian relations as very good, saying
that there are vast horizons for the economic cooperation within
the framework of the existing joint ventures and the projects under
assessment, including one for assembling tractors.
</P>
<P>
The Romanian official said he and Mubarak also discussed ways of
expanding trade, the volume of which now stands at about 300
million U.S. dollars annually.
</P>
<P>
The two countries have agreed to make joint efforts to increase
the trade volume to 1 billion dollars in the coming few years, said
Roman, who arrived in Cairo on Monday for a three-day visit.
</P>
<P>
He said that one of the main issues tackled during the meeting
was the Middle East peace process and its recent developments,
stressing that all parties realize the importance of Egypt's role
in helping push forward the peace march.
</P>
<P>
Romania intends to organize a ministerial meeting between the
Organization of Security and Cooperation in Europe and its partners
in the Mediterranean basin, including Egypt, to enhance the
relationship between the two sides, he added.
</P>
<P>
Romania can play a role in promoting Egypt's interests in East
and Central Europe in view of Romania's unique location in the
region, he noted. 
</P>
</TEXT>
