<DOCNO> XIE20000418.0358 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Arabs Renew Support for Lebanon's Right to Resist Occupation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, April 18 (Xinhua) -- The Arab League on Tuesday
reiterated support for Lebanon's legitimate right to resist
occupation of part of its territory by Israel.
</P>
<P>
In a statement issued to mark the fourth anniversary of the Qana
carnage, the league called on the world community, especially the
United Nations, the United States and Russia, co-sponsors of the
Middle East peace process, to adopt all necessary measures to halt
Israeli continued attacks on Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
On April 18, 1996, Israeli armed forces killed a number of
Lebanese civilians, mostly children and women, in a refugee camp
while launching air strikes on southern Lebanon. Israel has been
launching incessant attacks on southern Lebanon since then.
</P>
<P>
The statement underlined the need for Israel to implement the U.
N. Security Council resolution 425 to immediately and
unconditionally pull out from all Lebanese lands to the
internationally recognized borders.
</P>
<P>
Israel invaded Lebanon in 1978 to drive Palestinian fighters out
of the country. Following the Israeli invasion of Lebanon, the U.N.
Security Council passed resolutions 425 and 426, calling for
immediate and unconditional Israeli withdrawal from Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
But Israel at that time refused to abide by the resolutions,
instead, it carved up a border strip in 1985 as a security zone to
allegedly protect its northern areas from cross-border attacks by
Lebanese Muslim guerrillas.
</P>
<P>
However, in a bid to pull out of the mire, Israel decided in
early March that it will withdraw its troops from south Lebanon by
July under the two U.N. resolutions, even without agreements with
Lebanon and Syria, the main power broker in Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
The Arab League also urged Israel to release all Lebanese
captives and detainees held in its prisons and detention camps.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000418.0359 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, April 18 (Xinhua) -- The following are economic briefs
from the Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
KHARTOUM -- The Khartoum Oil Refinery at Jily started test
operation on Tuesday, the Sudanese News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The full operation of all units of the refinery will start in
the coming few weeks, producing different oil products at a total
capacity of 50,000 barrels a day.
</P>
<P>
The production will meet all Sudan's needs of oil products and
gas.
</P>
<P>
ANKARA -- All preparations have been completed for the
construction of a ship traffic observation and control system in
the Turkish Straits, reported the Anatolia News Agency on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The Maritime Undersecretariat will be responsible for the
project and the United States Lockheed Martin Co. will undertake
the construction of the system.
</P>
<P>
Officials of the Maritime Undersecretariat said that as the
Government Accounting Bureau has approved the project, the
construction will go ahead soon.
</P>
<P>
They expected that with the new system in operation in 2001,
most of sea accidents will be prevented.
</P>
<P>
TEHRAN -- Iran exported over 2.5 million tons of metals and
minerals valued at 445 million U.S. dollars last Iranian year,
which ended on March 19, said Mines and Metals Minister Eshaq
Jahangiri on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
He told reporters that in 2,183 active mines, excluding sand and
gravel, 106 million tons of minerals were extracted last year.
</P>
<P>
The minister added that 1.2 billion dollars of steel contracts
was signed last year. The figure this Iranian year is expected to
surpass one billion dollars, almost the same level as last year.
</P>
<P>
TEHRAN -- Iran's Minister of Agriculture Issa Kalantari on
Tuesday voiced his concern about drought, saying the country is not
well prepared to confront the threat.
</P>
<P>
Addressing ministry officials, he said last year was the worst
in the past 30 years in terms of precipitation, with the level of
water resources falling to 70 billion cubic meters in the
precipitation season from September 1999 to early 2000.
</P>
<P>
The government should not limit its duties to giving aid to
farmers affected by drought and debt relief, he stressed, adding
that the main way of coping with the drought is to invest in the
agricultural sector. 
</P>
</TEXT>
