<HEADLINE> Italian Prime Minister to Address Senate over His Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
D'Alema offered his resignation to President Carlo Azeglio
Ciampi Monday evening, after his center-left coalition lost the
key vote on Sunday, but Ciampi told him to return to parliament to
resolve his crisis.
</P>
<P>
A debate is expected to follow D'Alema's appearance in the
Senate and should conclude the same day, Italian news agency Ansa
reported.
</P>
<P>
The consensus among observers is that D'Alema does not intend
to remain in office nor does he want to see parliament dissolved,
which would meet the Opposition's demand for snap elections.
</P>
<P>
Among the alternatives to elections is a new center-left
government headed by someone else in the coalition, in which case
Treasury Minister Giuliano Amato appears the most likely candidate,
or an"institutional" executive headed by Senate speaker Nicola
Mancino which would run government at least through next month's
referendum vote and perhaps into the Autumn, at most, the end of
the legislature next spring.
</P>
<P>
The center-left on Sunday saw its previous 9-6 advantage in the
regions reversed to a 7-8 disadvantage, a loss of three including
the key central region of Lazio and the northeast region of
Liguria, which gave the Freedom Front, allied with the Northern
league, total control of the wealthy and industrial north.
</P>
<P>
According to an estimate of national voting, the Freedom Front
with North League got 50.7 percent of the vote while the center-
left plus  the hard-left Communist Re-foundation party got 45.1
percent.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Italian former premier, the European Commission
President Romano Prodi Tuesday ruled out the possibility of
returning to Italy to replace Massimo D'Alema as head of a new
center-left government.
</P>
<P>
Prodi's spokesman Jonathan Faull told the press in Brussels
that it is unthinkable that the president would return to Italy.
</P>
</TEXT>
