<HEADLINE> Colombian Rebel ELN Frees 8 Hostages </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BOGOTA, April 18 (Xinhua) -- The Colombian Rebel National
Liberation Army (ELN)  left free Tuesday five crew members and
three passengers of a commercial plane kidnapped a year ago.
</P>
<P>
A humanitarian commission made up by three Colombian officials
and a delegate of the Red Cross International Committee received
the hostages in a jungle of Bolivar department in the north of the
country.
</P>
<P>
On April 12, 1999, a group of five ELN guerrillas kidnapped a
plane of Avianca company while it was flying over the area between
Bucaramanga in the northeast and Bogota. The rebels formed part of
the plane's 46 passengers.
</P>
<P>
The ELN left free 26 of the passengers captured on the plane,
one perished, and is keeping six following those freed this
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The rebel group, Colombia's second biggest, said that due to
the religious date of Holy Week it declared a unilateral truce
that entered into force last Thursday and will end at midnight
next Sunday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
