<DOCNO> XIE20000418.0366 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: UN Sanctions on Rebels Crucial for Angolan Peace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, April 18 (Xinhua) -- Angolan foreign minister Joao
Miranda will urge the U.N Security Council to reinforce sanctions
against the Angolan rebels in his address on Tuesday to the
Council session on the implementation of the sanctions.
</P>
<P>
Local analysts said the full implementation of the sanctions
will be vital to end the 26-year bloody war in the southwest
African country.
</P>
<P>
With abundant natural resources of oil and diamonds, Angola has
 great potential for economic development. But until today, its
still in a dream of the Angolans.
</P>
<P>
Decades-long civil conflicts has killed hundreds of thousands
Angolans and hindered the economic development in the country. And
the conflict is believed to be fueled by the failure of the
implementation of the UN sanctions on the rebels.
</P>
<P>
The UN has imposed sanctions on the National Union for the
Total Independence of Angola (UNITA) rebels led by Jonas Savimbi
since September 1993, including arms and diamond embargo, a ban on
travelling abroad for UNITA officials and their relatives, closure
of the organization's offices out of the countries.
</P>
<P>
However, the sanctions failed to prevent the rebels from
purchasing weapons with diamond trade from the black markets, and
the rebels have got much more revenue than the government from the
diamond mines, which supported their war machine.
</P>
<P>
Chairman of the UN Sanction Committee on Angola, Robert Fowler,
made a report after a 30-country tour and a field investigation,
recommending punishment for the violators of the UN sanctions and
the creation of mechanisms of control.
</P>
<P>
Before leaving Luanda for New York, Angolan Foreign Minister
Miranda said that he would urge the member countries of the
Security Council to agree on the recommendations in the report
issued in March, which identified several countries that violated
the sanctions.
</P>
<P>
Once the UN sanctions are effectively enforced, the rebels will
lose logistic support, and be forced to negotiate with the
government for a political solution.
</P>
<P>
At that moment, the Angolan government can spend more time and
money for the national reconstruction and the economic
development. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000418.0367 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-18 </DATE_TIME>
