<HEADLINE> EU Decides to Start WTO Case with Chile </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, April 18 (Xinhua) -- The European Union (EU)
executive body Tuesday decided to start World Trade Organization (
WTO) dispute settlement procedures against Chile over a swordfish
row.
</P>
<P>
The European Commission said in a statement that the decision
will challenge Chile's unilateral ban on vessels of the EU
countries unloading swordfish catches in Chilean ports, which has
existed since 1991.
</P>
<P>
The decision to request consultations with Chile has been taken
after an investigation under the Trade Barriers Regulation (TBR)
revealed that the Chilean measures contravene WTO rules, the EU
executive said, adding it has taken this step with a view to
securing free and fair access to Chilean ports for EU vessels.
</P>
<P>
The Commission estimates that the injury suffered by the
fishermen from EU member states could be evaluated at around seven
million euros (about 6.7 million U.S. dollars) annually.
</P>
<P>
"In addition, the Chilean measures render impossible the
importation of the affected catches into Chile and prevent access
to certain important markets, like the United States, which import
a considerable quantity of fresh swordfish from Chile," the
Commission said.
</P>
<P>
Since the first stage of WTO dispute settlement proceedings
consists in a consultation period, the Commission said it is
hopeful that an amicable solution can be reached with the Chilean
side without the need to proceed to a panel. 
</P>
</TEXT>
