<HEADLINE> Security Council to Tighten Monitoring UNITA </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Angola has been engulfed in civil war almost continuously since
1975. Beginning in 1993, the Security Council imposed a series of
sanctions against UNITA as a means to pressure it to implement its
peace obligations.
</P>
<P>
The sanctions include oil and arms embargo, restrictions on the
travel of senior UNITA officials, freezing of UNITA funds and
prohibition of flights of aircraft by or for UNITA.
</P>
<P>
But there have been reports of UNITA violation of sanctions,
resulting in deteriorating situation in the African country,
featured by refugee influx along border areas with Namibia and
Zambia. The number of war-affected Angolans has grown to 3.7
million out of a total of 12.6 million, U.N. figures show.
</P>
<P>
The resolution requests U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan to
set up a monitoring mechanism for further investigation into the
alleged violations with a view to improving the implementation of
the sanctions.
</P>
<P>
The resolution asks U.N. member states to consider the proposal
to convene one or more conferences of representatives of arms
manufacturing and exporting countries to stem the illicit flow of
arms into Angola.
</P>
<P>
It encourages the convening of a conference of experts to
devise a regime for curbing the illegal supply of petroleum
products into UNITA-controlled areas. 
</P>
</TEXT>
