<HEADLINE> U.N. Chief Urges Zimbabwe's President to Defuse Tension </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, April 18 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Secretary-General
Kofi Annan on Tuesday urged Robert Mugabe, President of Zimbabwe,
to take measures to defuse tension over land reform, U.N.
spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
U.N. spokesman Fred Eckhard said Annan and Mugabe had a
telephone conversation today and discussed the issue.
</P>
<P>
Annan urged the President to take steps to defuse the tension,
Eckhard said.
</P>
<P>
"The Secretary-General is glad to know that the President will
again be meeting with representatives of the farmers and the
veterans tomorrow, and that he has decided to send a ministerial-
level delegation to London on April 27 to discuss the land issue,"
the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
The United Nations deplored the violence in Zimbabwe and it
was monitoring the situation for a while and would continue to
monitor it closely, the spokesman added.
</P>
<P>
According to reports reaching here, thousands of veterans of
the 1970s liberation war have occupied hundreds of white-owned
farms which turned violent last week when invaders began to beat
farmers. Two farmers have been killed in recent days.  
</P>
</TEXT>
