<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Wall Street Stocks Rebound Again </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
At the close of session, the Dow Jones industrial average rose
184.91 at 10,767.42, extending its gain of 276.74 points Monday.
</P>
<P>
The technology heavy Nasdaq composite index also rose 254.41 at
3,793.57. The composite rebounded 217.87 points Monday from last
week's jolt.
</P>
<P>
The stocks rallied as investors continued moving into market
for bargain-hunting. Sun Microsystems, Microsoft and Cisco Systems
led the Nasdaq's advance.
</P>
<P>
The bounce-back were spread across the market and therefore
advancing issues led decliners. In the previous session, most
stocks fell despite a strong rebound for most indexes.
</P>
<P>
A big selloff hit the stock market last Friday in fears of
rising inflation after the Labor Department reported a sharp rise
in the March Consumer Price Index. The Dow index lost 617.78
points while the Nasdaq composite fell 355.49 points.
</P>
<P>
Broader stock indicators were also higher today. The Standard &AMP;
Poor's 500 index rose 40.17 at 1,441.61 and the NYSE index rose 14.
60 at 634.81.
</P>
<P>
The American Stock Exchange index rose 28.39 at 877.36 while
the Russell 2000 index of smaller companies rose 26.81 at 486.09.
</P>
<P>
Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by a 2-to-1 margin on
the New York Stock Exchange, with 1,990 up, 1,016 down and 442
unchanged.
</P>
<P>
NYSE volume declined to 1.09 billion shares from 1.29 billion
in the previous session. 
</P>
</TEXT>
